<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Plans Student Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
is planning a massive expansion of universities and colleges over
the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
Blair, who put education at heart of New Labor's election
manifesto, wants at least 50 percent of all people under the age
of 30 to take part in higher education, according to a report from
The Guardian newspaper Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the new places would be on part-time courses, so
students could learn at the same time as working or looking after
a family.
</P>
<P>
A Department for Education spokesman confirmed there were plans
under way to look at how to achieve a large-scale expansion of
college and university places. The figure of 50 percent would
include part-time students and flexible courses, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Education Secretary David Blunkett has already set a target of
35 percent of 18- to 21-year-olds studying in higher education by
2002.
</P>
<P>
A more ambitious target would be likely to become part of the
government's promises for a second term in office, according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
Last week the Higher Education Funding Council for England
announced this year's university funding settlement, which
included an extra 95 million pounds (about 160 million U.S.
dollars) to help widen access to degree courses to students from
poorer families.
</P>
<P>
The new money would be spent over two years on improving the
training of managers and lecturers, modernizing equipment and
buildings, and widening participation in further education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
