<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Coordinator Reviews DPRK Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. envoy William Perry said Monday
the conclusion of his report on the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) will be made in full harmony with South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at Seoul Kimpo International Airport, Perry, the U.
S. coordinator on DPRK policy, said in a arrival statement that
the South Korean government's viewpoint is an essential condition
for making U.S. DPRK policy.
</P>
<P>
Perry was appointed as the coordinator to review the Clinton
Administration's DPRK policy in accordance with the 1994 nuclear
agreement signed in Geneva amid increasing criticism by the
Republican-led House of Representatives of the agreement after
Pyongyang's successful launch of a satellite.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. defense secretary said he is still making an
overall review of the DPRK policy and that he has not yet made a
final report to President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton wants to know South Korean President Kim Dae-
jung's view on the DPRK policy, said Perry, who is expected to
meet Kim Dae-jung, Foreign Minister Hong Soon-young and other
South Korean senior officials.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Perry pointed out that engagement is a
positive element of a policy basis Seoul and Washington should
make and Clinton voiced his support of it at his two meetings with
Kim last year.
</P>
<P>
However, in his recently published book titled "Preventive
Defense", Perry expressed his concern over President Kim Dae-jung'
s "sunshine policy" which seeks reconciliation, exchanges and
cooperation with the DPRK based on separating economics from
politics.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the book clearly shows the differences between
the United States and South Korea on the DPRK issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
