<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO General Complains of Bloc Split Over Kosovo Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- A top NATO official Monday accused
some political leaders in the 15-nation bloc of undermining the
Alliance's ability to take action against Yugoslavia over the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
NATO Military Committee chairman General Klaus Naumann,
addressing a London conference, said unnamed leaders of the bloc
were giving Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic "guarantees that
certain things won't happen."
</P>
<P>
NATO has threatened to strike at Serb forces in and around
Kosovo if Belgrade is deemed to be blocking a deal to end the
conflict in the ethnic Albanian region of Serbia, although some
member states are not altogether comfortable with the idea, a
Reuters report said.
</P>
<P>
"I am unhappy that some of our Alliance leaders are giving
President Slobodan Milosevic guarantees that certain things won't
happen, so he can play chess with us," Naumann was quoted by
Reuters as telling a conference marking NATO's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Such guarantees made it harder for NATO to keep Milosevic
guessing as to what the Alliance might do, he said. "Everyone
should rest assured that anyone who dares to raise his weapons
against NATO will not have a good time in the long run. This
uncertainty has to remain and we will remain free to use all
instruments in our quiver so that anyone should know uncertainty
is a factor of risk calculation."
</P>
<P>
Naumann refused to say as to what measures NATO might be
prepared to take against Belgrade next, noting that "one should
never try to answer this question precisely in advance. Everyone
should know that this Alliance will use all the instruments it has
as soon as it is threatened." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
