<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Lets Kurdish's Party to Run in Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's highest court Monday
rejected an appeal lodged by the Court of Appeals demanding the
closure of a Kurdish party and ban on its participation in the
upcoming April 18 elections.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Constitutional Court said the
People's Democracy Party, which is allegedly linked to the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), can run in the local and
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The ruling was reached following a four-hour-long meeting on
the appeal raised by Chief Prosecutor Vural Savas that aimed at
putting an end to the Kurdish party.
</P>
<P>
The HADEP has strong opportunities in the local elections in
the Kurdish-dominated southeast, where the PKK has been waging a
15-year-old war for independence despite the capture of its
leader, Abdullah Ocalan, by Turkish authorities.
</P>
<P>
Savas charged that the HADEP was operating as a branch of the
PKK and accused it of inciting separatism based on ethnic lines
and enlisting volunteers for the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Savas cited a nationwide hunger strike staged by the HADEP
members last November in support the PKK as evidence.
</P>
<P>
The HADEP may face closure if the Constitutional Court rules in
the future that it has close ties with the PKK, deemed a
separatist terrorist group by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Since 1983, Turkey's Constitutional Court has banned 14
political parties for various reasons, arousing European concerns
over its human rights record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
