<HEADLINE> UK Government Announces Delay in N.Irish Power Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The British government announced
Monday a three-week delay until March 29 for forming a new
home-rule executive in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the delay, Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam
told a news conference Monday, "This gives the parties the time
and space to find a way forward."
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland secretary had originally set March 10 as
the deadline for transfer of power from London, but a dispute over
Irish Republican Army (IRA) disarmament has held up the creation
of a new power-sharing cabinet composed of Protestant and Roman
Catholic politicians.
</P>
<P>
The proposed handover is seen as an important part of last
year's "Good Friday" peace deal, intended to draw a line under 30
years of political and sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
As many Northern Ireland politicians would be visiting the
United States next week for St Partick's Day celebrations, "there
will be opportunities to build confidence and talk informally
together, ready for an intensive round of discussions when they
return to Belfast," Mowlam was quoted by Reuters as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam made it clear that it was up to the parties to ensure
the success of the new executive, saying "power can only be
transferred and exercised with cross-community support." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
