<HEADLINE> Ugandan Women's Status Improved: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said Monday that women's status in the east African country has
been greatly improved in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Museveni made the remarks when addressing a public rally
marking the International Women's Day in the southwestern district
of Mbarara, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the recently enacted land law has several
provisions aimed at empowering women to fight poverty and that the
government has increased the number of women in leadership
positions.
</P>
<P>
The government has launched a poverty alleviation action plan
which has focused on five sectors including improvement of road
network and establishment of sound food marketing structures, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The president acknowledged that poverty still constitutes a big
threat to the country and urged leaders at all levels to make
poverty elimination a priority task.
</P>
<P>
Women account for 51 percent of Uganda's population. However,
female illiteracy rates in rural and urban areas is 55 percent and
26 percent respectively, much higher than their male counterparts
in either case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
