<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Secret Deal in Pak-India Talks: FM Aziz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz said here Monday that there was no secret deal with
India during Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee's visit to
Pakistan last month.
</P>
<P>
Making a policy statement at the Senate on Vajpayee's visit,
Aziz said that Pakistan would not compromise on its principled
stand on the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
There was no secret understanding or deal during the talks
between Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his Indian counterpart
Vajpayee, the foreign minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Vajpayee himself underlined the need to resolve
the long-standing Kashmir dispute through bilateral process in his
three public announcements during his two-day stay in Lahore on
February 20-21.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Lahore Declaration signed by the prime
ministers of Pakistan and India, Aziz said the document
establishes the commitment of both sides to intensify their
efforts to resolve the outstanding issue of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"It is our conviction that the government policy of engaging
with India at the highest level has better served the Kashmir
cause," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the most significant outcome of the Pak-India
Summit has been the agreement between the two prime ministers to
intensify the efforts for the resolution of the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
The Lahore Declaration, Aziz said, also underscores the
commitment of both sides to the principles and purposes of the
U.N. charter as well as reiterating their determination to
implement the Simla agreement in letter and spirit.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that peace, progress and prosperity in South Asia are
not possible without an environment of security and stability, for
which purpose it is imperative to resolve the Kashmir dispute, the
root cause of tensions in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
