<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, EU Criticized at WTO Special Meeting Over Banana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Both the United States and the
European Union have been criticized for their handling of the
escalating banana dispute at a special meeting of the General
Council of the World Trade Organization (WTO), according to trade
officials here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was called at the European Union's request last
Thursday when the United States ordered importers to post deposits
against selected EU goods in anticipation of the possible
imposition of 100 percent duties.
</P>
<P>
An overwhelming majority of the 134 WTO members, including the
Latin American countries associated with the U.S. in the banana
dispute, said that the U.S. unilateral action was not consistent
with the rule of the multilateral trading system.
</P>
<P>
Many also complained that the "extraordinary meeting" of the
General Council at the EU's request in such short notice was a
"source of frustrations."
</P>
<P>
Usually members should have 10 days's notice to hold a special
meeting of the General Council, the WTO's governing body.
</P>
<P>
In their statements at the closed-door meeting, WTO members
said that they thought the banana dispute between the U.S. and the
EU should be resolved at a meeting of the organization's Dispute
Settlement Body rather than the decision-making body.
</P>
<P>
The world is "mesmerized" by the dispute even though EU-U.S.
trade amounts to only 5 percent of the global market, Canadian
Ambassador John Weekes was reported as saying. The WTO should be
focusing on the other 95 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
WTO members urged the two "most powerful members" to show
leadership in settling their trade dispute and not to take any
"additional unnecessary actions."
</P>
<P>
No decisions have been taken during the one-day meeting, the
trade officials told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
