<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Withdraws Charge Against Swiss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 8 (Xinhua) -- A South African court Monday
dropped a charge of unlawful possession of the country's state
secret document against a Swiss journalist.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the South African prosecution, the Cape Town
Magistrate's Court informed Swiss TV journalist Jean-Philippe
Ceppi that the charge has been withdrawn and he is free, South
African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Ceppi was arrested last Friday in Cape Town for alleged illegal
 possession of a top secret military intelligence document, the
contents of which have so far remained a mystery. The police said
Ceppi's arrest followed a request by military intelligence agents.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss national and a colleague were in South Africa to
investigate the role of Swiss banks in the former apartheid
government.
</P>
<P>
Ceppi's lawyer said Monday after his release that the charge
was withdrawn because there had been no basis for it.
</P>
<P>
He said in terms of South African law, a prosecution concerning
military intelligence cannot go ahead without an order of the
Directorate of Public Prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
However, having heard all relevant representations, Western
Cape Director of Public Prosecutions, Frank Kahn, decided there
was no case.
</P>
<P>
The documents in question have been returned to Ceppi, a
further proof that they are public documents, Ceppi's lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
Ceppi has not decided on whether to launch a civil action for
alleged unlawful arrest, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
Swiss ambassador to South Africa Robert Mayor, who attended
Ceppi's hearing Monday, said he understood the reason for Ceppi's
arrest but did not want to get involved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
