<HEADLINE> World Bank Urges Partnership in Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Monday called on
countries to decentralize developmental activities by adopting
comprehensive frameworks through which they can link themselves to
local and global institutions.
</P>
<P>
Macro-economic management and policy division manager of the
World Bank Ishac Diwan told a capacity building workshop in Harare
that governments should be more open to work with the private
sector and the civil society.
</P>
<P>
He said that countries should be in the driving seat of their
own development programs.
</P>
<P>
He said it was imperative for governments, international
organizations and civic society to work in partnership for
development to take place.
</P>
<P>
"It is important for countries to have knowledge for long term
visions rather than having short term and myopic plans as is
usually the case with politicians," he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, he said, had started a comprehensive
development framework pilot project with Ethiopia, Ghana, Bolivia
and Turkey which would later be extended to other countries if
successful.
</P>
<P>
The capacity building workshop is being attended by more than
50 representatives of economic research institutes and foundations
from sub- Saharan Africa, as well as Germany, Lebanon, Poland and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
It is being held under the theme: "Think tanks as policy
catalysts in Africa: A capacity building workshop". It will run
for three days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
