<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Injured in U.S.-British Warplane Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 8 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi citizen was injured in
U.S. and British air raids against a number of civilian facilities
on Monday, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 9:50 a.m. local time (0650 GMT), 11
formations of F-14, F-15 and F-16 warplanes supported by early
warning AWACS from the Turkish airspace violated Iraqi airspace
over Neineva, Erbil and Dohuk provinces.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes shelled civilian targets and anti-aircraft
artillery positions, injuring one Iraqi citizen, he said. He did
not say whether the injured is a military personnel or a civilian.
</P>
<P>
"Our anti-aircraft defenses challenged the hostile warplanes
and forced them to flee, returning to their bases at 2 p.m. local
time (1100 GMT)," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that at 11:15 a.m. local time (0815 GMT), hostile
formations coming from Kuwaiti and Saudi bases violated Iraqi
airspace over Dhi-Qar, Wassit, Misan and al-Muthana provinces.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between Iraqi air defense forces and U.S. and British
jets patrolling the no-fly zones have almost become a daily
occurrence since the mid-December U.S.-British bombardment of
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed after the 1991 Gulf War by the
U.S.-led western allies with a claimed aim of protecting the Kurds
in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from "Baghdad's
suppression." 
</P>
</TEXT>
