<HEADLINE> Khatami Urges OIC to Deal Problems More Actively </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
here on Monday called for a more active role by the Organization
of the Islamic Conference (OIC) in dealing with the problems of
the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with the OIC Secretary General Azeddine Laraki,
Khatami called on the Islamic body to pay more attention to the
issues of Palestine, Iraq, Libya and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Having a general knowledge of problems in the world of Islam
helps with addressing the specific problems of each Muslim state,
he was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, who is also current OIC chairman, called on Laraki to
try to bring Muslim states closer to each other.
</P>
<P>
He cited expansion of dialogue and understanding among the
member states as the main achievement of the organization since
Iran took over the chairmanship in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Through a dialogue among Muslim scholars and relying on
commonalities, Muslim states should become fully prepared to
enter the year 2001, designated as the year of dialogue among
civilizations," Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations last year approved Khatami's proposal to
name the year 2001 as the year of dialogue among civilizations.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Laraki termed dialogue among civilizations as a
very rich idea which is yet to be fully understood in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Laraki arrived here on Friday night for a four-day visit to
present a report on the organization's activities to the OIC
chairman, the implementation of OIC resolutions in
particular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
