<HEADLINE> Pirate Radio Owner Charged with Incitement in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The owner of a pirate radio
station in Israel was charged in the Jerusalem District Court
Monday with incitement after calling for the murder of left-wing
Meretz party leader Yossi Sarid.
</P>
<P>
Yisrael Bundak, calling Sarid anti-religious, threatened to
kill him in a broadcast last Friday. He was also charged with
running an illegal radio station, the pirate Voice of the East,
Israel TV reported.
</P>
<P>
Bundak defended himself by insisting that the death threat was
only "a joke" in the Jewish joy holiday of Purim, but Sarid said
it has crossed the "red line" in domestic debate.
</P>
<P>
Meretz is a left-wing secular party famous for its opposition
to what it calls the religious coercion by ultra-Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
The death threat came a week after the parliament passed a
legislation legalizing un-licensed pirate radio stations which had
been broadcasting for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
Hearing five petitions against the legislation, the Supreme
Court issued a compromise order Monday, halting the legalization
proceedings for two weeks to give the supporters of the
legislation more time to respond to the petitions.
</P>
<P>
Two of the five petitions were filed by the Meretz party,
including one from Sarid.
</P>
<P>
After the death of late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who was
killed by an ultra-nationalist in 1995, Israelis have urged the
government to take tough measures to curb incitement of violence
against politicians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
