<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Increasingly Claims Girls, Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Girls and women are
becoming the principal victims of the rampant HIV/AIDS pandemic in
the developing world, the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion of observing International Women's
Day, UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy said, "What was once a
predominantly male disease has become a heterosexual-spread
pandemic which is now consigning tens of millions of girls and
women to a cruel, slow death due to AIDS."
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said the spread of HIV/AIDS among girls and women is
taking place amid an atmosphere of pervasive gender-based
discrimination, and some 73 million girls worldwide are denied the
right to education and the majority of the world's 1 billion
illiterates are female.
</P>
<P>
Deprived of the opportunity to receive an education and to
participate in their societies as equals to men, millions of girls
are relegated to subsistence and domestic chores instead of
attending school and building a future, the UNICEF head said.
</P>
<P>
The challenge posed by the spreading HIV/AIDS epidemic among
girls and women involves issues of basic human rights and urgently
requires adequate services to prevent the spread of HIV, Bellamy
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are faced with age-old cultural values which have
subordinated women and denied them the same rights as have been
accorded to men. the resulting widespread abuse and discrimination
are nowhere more clearly evident than in the chilling fact that
huge members of socially powerless women are being infected with
HIV by their husbands," Bellamy said.
</P>
<P>
"Hand in hand with the battle to defeat HIV/AIDS, we need to
endure that girls and women are accorded full equality in all
areas of life," Bellamy added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for End to Violence Against Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday called for an end to violence against women in the
world at large, but he acknowledged that "much remains to be done"
to reach the goal.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Inter-Agency Videoconference for a World Free
of Violence Against Women, Annan said, "Each of us must accept
responsibility for stamping out gender-based violence. We must
ensure that there are legal framework and institutions capable of
dealing with in."
</P>
<P>
"We must ensure that violence is recognized and condemned, and
that those who perpetrate it do not go unpunished," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Ultimately, it is up to all of us -- in our homes, our
communities, our nations, our global community -- to create a
world that is safe for women and girls: in which all women have
full enjoyment of all human rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remarks as the United Nations is celebrating the
last International Women's Day of the 20th century, which falls on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"During this century, human rights have been recognized in law
and guaranteed in international agreements. During this century,
humanity has learnt that the enjoyment of human rights is
essential to the well-being and development of the individual, the
community and the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And yet, too many women are still denied these basic human
rights," he said. "Too often, their liberty and dignity are
compromised. And too many of them are subjected to violence."
</P>
<P>
"Violence against women is perhaps the most shameful human
rights violation. And it is perhaps the most pervasive," he said.
"It knows no boundaries of geography, culture of wealth."
</P>
<P>
"As long as it continues, we cannot claim to be making real
progress towards equality, development and peace," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
