<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Fix A Common Written Language for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique will have a standard
written language for all ethnic groups this year, the Minister of
Culture, Youth and Sports, Jose Mateus Muaria Katupha, said in
capital Maputo Monday.
</P>
<P>
Katupha revealed this while attending the opening ceremony for
the second National Ethnic Languages Standardization Seminar.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that it is not an easy job to require various
ethnic groups to use a common written language.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that there might be disputes over what will
be fixed as a standard written language. He appealed decision
makers to be less emotional when they work to settle this problem.
</P>
<P>
At present, Mozambique's official language is Portuguese, but
the southern African country has a diversity of ethnic languages,
most of which do not have their own written languages.
</P>
<P>
Katupha expressed beliefs that the five-day seminar,
co-sponsored by the ministry and the University of Eduardo
Mondlane, will produce a significant impact on Mozambique's new
ways of writing.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that Radio Mozambique should play an important
role in popularizing ethnic tongues by broadcasting news and
programs in these languages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
