<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Ramblers Promised Right to Roam Over Private Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- British Environment Minister
Michael Meacher has promised ramblers a statutory right to roam
over 4 million acres of land in England and Wales, which has been
denied them up till now.
</P>
<P>
In a Commons statement he told members of parliament Monday,
"We are now convinced legislation is the only way to make sure
people will be free in perpetuity to explore open countryside."
</P>
<P>
He said the government recognized landowners' concerns and
walkers would not have the right to trample over crops and
gardens. Strict controls would also be introduced on dogs, the
environment minister said.
</P>
<P>
Legislation will be introduced as soon as parliamentary time
allows and will cover mountains, moor, heaths and downs and may be
extended to woodland.
</P>
<P>
"Securing greater access to open countryside will bring
tremendous benefits," Meacher was quoted by BBC as saying, and
"new opportunities for improving people's health, physical and
mental."
</P>
<P>
"And it will enable everyone to experience the wonders of
wildlife and beautiful landscapes," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Conservative Party attacked the proposals, which they say
will satisfy neither ramblers nor landowners.
</P>
<P>
Shadow Environment Secretary Gillian Shephard demanded
compensation arrangements for landowners who may suffer loss of
value to their property after being compelled to open it up.
</P>
<P>
"It will be cumbersome, it will be bureaucratic, it will
further divide town and countryside, and it is a squandered
opportunity," she said.
</P>
<P>
The right to roam is a tribute to former Labor leader John
Smith and the government promised legislation guaranteeing a right
to roam over open countryside when it was in opposition. Since
taking office, it has held consultations on how to increase
access.
</P>
<P>
The Country Landowners' Association says it supports the idea
that people should have greater freedom to explore open
countryside, but opposes the change in the law.
</P>
<P>
But the association is anxious to preserve "the right of owners
to choose how best to satisfy public demands for improved
countryside access, while safeguarding their land management
interests, wildlife and the environment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
