<HEADLINE> Russian Scientists Patent New AIDS Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian scientists have patented a
drug that they believe can rid blood of the AIDS virus but keeps
blood cells intact, the Interfax news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Interfax, quoting an evening newspaper in Novosibirsk, Siberia,
said the drug, developed by a local research center, rids blood of
immunodefficiency viruses in three to four days after
intravenously injection into the patient.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Lelyak, holder of the patent, said that the new
technology may be the basis for the development of a cure for HIV
carriers or AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have successfully tested the anti-AIDS technique in
laboratory conditions and have detected no viruses in the blood
after injections of the drug, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
