<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNFPA Chief Calls for Zero Tolerance of Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Naif Sadik, executive
director of the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), Monday
called for zero tolerance of violence against women, saying
perpetrators of violence against women worldwide must be held
accountable for their actions.
</P>
<P>
All too often, the perpetrators receive light sentences or are
excused with a reference to family honor, she said, encouraging
all governments, non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and civil
society including the private sector to work for an end to all
violence against women.
</P>
<P>
Sadik made the remarks in delivering an address at the global
videoconference for "A World Free of Violence Against Women" on
the occasion of International Women's Day, which falls on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The very same biological function that ensures that societies
survive, thrive and reproduce is the very same one that makes
women the targets of violence," she said.
</P>
<P>
"It is time that everyone of us, individually and collectively,
takes a stand to eradicate violence against women in all its
manifestations," she said. "We must break the culture of silence
on violence against women. We must promote zero tolerance of
violence against women everywhere."
</P>
<P>
The 90-minute videoconference is held at the U.N. headquarters
Monday morning with the presence of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, who voiced in a speech his appeal for an end to violence
against women in the world at large.
</P>
<P>
"Women and girls are actually at greater risk of violence from
members of their households, than from strangers," Sadik said.
"Many forms of communally sanctioned violence against women, such
as female genital mutilation or honor killings, are associated
with the community's or the family's demand for sexual chastity
and virginity."
</P>
<P>
"Womens' and girls' reproductive and sexual health should not
depend on the perceptions and feelings of those wielding authority
over them, be they the State, the church, the community or the
family, but must be guaranteed as a basic human rights," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Violence against women knows no class, race, or age," she
said. "It exists across all socio-economic groups, and it is a
daily phenomenon in the lives of women throughout the world and
throughout their life circle."
</P>
<P>
"Even before they are born, girls suffer from the consequences
of a widely prevalent socio-cultural disposition that favors boys
over girls," she said.
</P>
<P>
"In some countries, a strong preference for boys leads to the
killing of girls children and selective abortion of female
foetuses," she said. "Where resources are scare, boys are often
more likely to receive enough food, education or adequate medical
care, which logically leads to poorer health in girls, and even to
higher mortality rates on their part."
</P>
<P>
The UNFPA is fighting violence against women in several ways:
by helping to establish women's health centers, supporting
violence counseling, and campaigning against female genital
mutilation where it persists.
</P>
<P>
Also, it has named Goodwill Ambassadors to call attention to
improve the status of women and point out the harmful effects of
violence on families, women and girls, as well as on society as a
whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
