<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Eliminating Violence against Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 8 (Xinhua) -- As part of the UN campaign to
eliminate violence against women worldwide, a regional conference
on Good Practices toward Eliminating Violence against Women and
Girls in Africa opened here Monday on the occasion of
International Women's Day.
</P>
<P>
Over 300 participants from more than 20 African countries as
well as the United States and France are attending the conference
organized by the UN Development Fund for Women (UNIFEM).
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, the participants will discuss on
such topics as actualizing the right to protection, innovative
strategies to eliminate specific forms of violence against women,
good practices in dealing with gender-based violence in
situations of conflict and reconstruction, and African men's
initiative to eliminate violence against women and girls.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, Attorney-General Amos Wako of
Kenya said, "our campaign to eliminate violence against women is
at the heart of the struggle for the survival of civilization."
</P>
<P>
Wako pointed out that in the process to eliminate violence
against women,
</P>
<P>
all levels of the society must be engaged in changing attitudes
and behavior particularly on the part of men.
</P>
<P>
He said Kenyan government is committed to eradicating violence
against women, and conference like this could help Kenya to put
in place appropriate legislation and strategies to combat
violence against women.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the conference was coincided with a UN
inter-agency global video conference entitled "A World Free of
Violence Against Women", the first of its kind ever to be held in
the UN General Assembly Hall.
</P>
<P>
The 90-minute video conference linked five sites, Strasbourg in
France, Mexico City in Mexico, Nairobi in Kenya, New Delhi in
India and New York. It features women whose personal experiences
of violence have inspired policies and strategies to eliminate
gender violence.
</P>
<P>
The video conference discussed such issues as domestic
violence, trafficking in women and girls, harmful traditional
practices including dowry deaths and female genital mutilation,
and wartime violence against women including rape and sex
slavery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
