<HEADLINE> Ugandan Women Poor Despite Contribution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has said that women in the country are still the poorest of the
poor in spite of the major role they play in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The president made the statement Monday when addressing the
nation on the occasion of International Women's Day in Mbarara
municipality, 270 km southwest of capital city Kampala.
</P>
<P>
Museveni attributed women's poor status to lack of access to
productive resources, unequal distribution of wealth and very
limited levels of awareness and information.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan women, who constitute 51 percent of the population,
produce 80 percent of the food, 60 percent of the cash crops and
contribute 70 percent of the agricultural labor force, but own
only seven percent of the land.
</P>
<P>
Museveni urged women to be facilitated to increase the volume
of their economic activities in all the sectors of the economy in
which they are engaged.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase women's sense of ownership, especially in
rural areas, they should have a say in the disposal of land and,
most importantly, own the matrimonial home jointly with their men,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
