<HEADLINE> Zambia Starts Reforms on Enrolment System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of new students entering
Zambia's two universities will almost be doubled this year
because the government has embarked on reforms to liberalize and
open entry into the universities.
</P>
<P>
Deputy permanent secretary of Education Ministry, Godwin
Chibesakunda, told Xinhua on Monday that the reforms will include
allowing more self- sponsored than the government-sponsored
students into the institutions of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
The move is intended to expand and diversify student enrolment
and cut down on excess demand for bursaries from the government.
</P>
<P>
He said the issue of introducing a loan scheme for students was
 receiving active consideration to establish cost implications,
adding that it was the ministry's objective to cut on direct
expenditure on student welfare through the reforms by at least 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the government will continue to be responsible for a
sizable part of funds for the two universities, he said.
</P>
<P>
After the reforms, the total of new students entering
Copperbelt University and the University of Zambia will increase
from last year's 1600 to 2700, he said.

