<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protein Holds Key of Cancers' Resistant to Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- British scientists said Monday they
were one step closer towards understanding why some cancers do not
respond to drug treatment.
</P>
<P>
The key to destroying drug-resistant tumors lies in a protein
molecule called Bak which prompts damaged cells self destruct,
Professor John Hickman and colleagues from the University of
Manchester have found.
</P>
<P>
The scientists believed their research will provide information
needed to find new ways to kill cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
Normally, a healthy cell will die when it reaches the end of
its life span or when it knows it's no longer needed. Cells that
are damaged will also "self destruct" as a safety mechanism so
their faults are not replicated in future generations.
</P>
<P>
However, cancer cells do not die in the usual way, and go on
reproducing themselves uncontrollably. Most conventional
treatments aim to force cancer cells to commit suicide by
inflicting further damage on them but some cancer cells can resist
this bombardment.
</P>
<P>
The Manchester team has found that the protein Bak receives
signals from the parts of the cell which assess and report damage
caused by drugs and it then makes the cell self destruct.
</P>
<P>
The researchers discovered that Bak is normally held in check
by another molecule. To become active, Bak must separate from this
"minder" and change shape.
</P>
<P>
Once it changes shape it can receive the signals that the cell
is damaged and commit it to die. The scientists believed this does
not happen in cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
"The next question we hope to answer is why Bak does not get
going in a cancer cell," Professor Hickman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"If we can find out why it doesn't, then in theory we could
find a way to jump-start it and force the cancer cell to die," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
