<HEADLINE> Bwindi Park to Open to Tourists Soon: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Bwindi National Park,
where eight foreign tourists were killed by Interahamwe rebels
last Monday, will reopen to tourists within a month's time, a
senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
Moses Ali, Second Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Tourism, Trade and Industry, made the pledge when visiting the
park to assess the damage in the area Monday, Radio Uganda
reported in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Everything is being done to ensure that the park reopens within
a month' s time, he added.
</P>
<P>
When addressing local people at a later time, the minister
cautioned them against allowing infiltrators into the country and
reminded them of their constitutional rights to defend their
country.
</P>
<P>
Bwindi Impenetrable Forest, topping the 10 national parks in
the country, is home to about 300 mountain gorillas, half of the
world's total population of that species.
</P>
<P>
The national park, which covers an area of 308 square
kilometers, is five km from Congo (K) border and is often regarded
as the first tourist attraction in the country.  
</P>
