<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian monetary authorities on Sunday adopted urgent
measures to control the abrupt rise of the exchange rate of the
U.S. dollar against the Egyptian pound (LE) as a result of larger
supply than demand.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Egypt (CBE) agreed to pump 2 billion
dollars of the CBE reserve that hits 20 billion dollars to cope
with the situation, the Arabic daily Al-Hayat quoted Chief of the
Egyptian Chambers of Commerce Federation (CCF) Mahmoud Al-Arabi as
saying.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The Iraqi dinar retreated against the U.S. dollar
shortly after the assassination of Mohammed Al-Sadr, a leading
Shiite leader in Najaf city late February.
</P>
<P>
The dinar exchange rate went down to 2,000 against a
U.S. dollar after the assassination, Al-Hayat reported. The
skyrocketing of the U.S. dollar exchange rate, which is
unprecedented in years, continued as unrest broke out.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and Syria have agreed to build a cement plant
, which will cost 180 million U.S. dollars, with an annual output
capacity of one million tonnes, Lebanese industry ministry sources
said this week.
</P>
<P>
The joint project will supply the local markets in Lebanon and
Syria. Any surplus may be exported, the sources said. 
</P>
