<HEADLINE> UNEP Launches Freshwater Communications Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) headquartered in Nairobi, capital of Kenya,
launched a freshwater communications campaign Monday with the
global release of a half-hour BBC television documentary.
</P>
<P>
The documentary, entitled "Everybody Lives Downstream", which
is to mark the World Water Day falling on March 22, focuses on
river basins on four continents and creates a symbolic river,
filmed in the Tibetan Plateau, the Colombian highlands, and on the
Nile and Rhine rivers.
</P>
<P>
"The film highlights the fact that when it comes to using
freshwater, human beings, whether they live in a village or a
mega-city, can not isolate themselves from their neighbors," said
Klaus Toepher, UNEP Executive Director, adding that there are
fundamental linkage and dependencies between water users and
users in a given drainage basin that affect everyone.
</P>
<P>
In the documentary, international experts and decision-makers
urge the public to back national and international efforts to
conserve the planet's limited water supplies.
</P>
<P>
The film, one of many information products pegged to a
communications campaign around World Water Day, will reach 135
million homes in 111 countries on BBC World Television, said the
UNEP official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
