<HEADLINE> Germany, Czech to Conclude "Final Treaty" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 8 (xinhua) -- Bonn and Prague will sign a "final
treaty" to resolve historic problems between the two countries as
German Federal Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and visiting Czech
Prime Minister Milos Zeman agreed after their Monday meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two also said ties between Germany and Czech should not be
disturbed by juridical or financial disputes.
</P>
<P>
The one-hour meeting focused on Czech's entry to the European
Union (EU), which has been fixed for next year.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder clearly refused demand of the expelled Sudetic
Germans, who required the German government to consider Czech's EU
membership after Prague returned their properties.
</P>
<P>
The requirement, as part of history, would not be borne by
Germany's foreign policy, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
After World War II, then Czechslovakian authorities expelled
ethnic Germans living in Sudetic region to Germany and confiscated
their properties.
</P>
<P>
Zeman and Schroeder said the German-Czech relationship should
aim at the future, but not the past, which cannot be changed.
</P>
