<HEADLINE> Angolan Women's Status Need to Improve: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- A cabinet minister in Angola
appealed on Monday to further improve the social status of women
in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Promotion for Family and Women, Candida Celeste
Da Silva,

made the appeal at a public rally in the capital Luanda to mark
the International Women's Day.
</P>
<P>
She said the legal equality between men and women in the
country is still not fully demonstrated, although a lot of women
are holding key work posts. Compared with their male colleagues,
women still take few important positions in the government or
other institutions.
</P>
<P>
In Angolan families, she said, it is still customary to let
boy go to school while girls are left at home doing household
chores, because in the eyes of parents the best life for a girl is
staying at home as a housewife.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she said women remain victims of domestic violence.
In the capital Luanda, a quarter of women are victims of violence
while in the rural areas the proportion is as high as 40 percent,
she said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said eruption of civil war in Angola again has
frustrated the country's women emancipation drive, adding that the
population of refugees in the country has increased by two
million, 80 percent of them are women and children.
</P>
<P>
She said the government has worked out strategies of improving
women's political, economic and social status, like extending
loans to them for creating enterprises and developing agriculture
and animal husbandry to help them escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
Other strategies include holding courses to reduce women
illiteracy rate, and banning violence against women, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
