<HEADLINE> Arafat on Declaration of Palestinian Statehood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
said here Monday that it is the Palestinian leadership that should
make decision on whether to declare statehood in early May.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority is contacting Arab States
and international parties on the issue, Arafat told a delegation
of the representation council of Jewish organization and community
in France.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had insisted that he would declare an independent
Palestinian state on May 4 when the transitional period under Oslo
accords expires, with or without Israeli consent.
</P>
<P>
Israel strong opposed the idea. Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu threatened to stop implementing the signed agreements
and annex parts of the West Bank if a Palestinian state is
unilaterally declared.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and European countries have been trying to persuade
Arafat to reach agreement with the Israelis before his next
move. So have some moderate Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here earlier in the day for consultations with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on a string of related issues.
"Peace is a strategic Arab choice and the Palestinians are keen on
realizing just and lasting peace," Arafat told the Jewish
delegation.
</P>
<P>
He had been scheduled to meet with Mubarak later Monday on
issues such as Palestinian statehood, situation on all tracks of
the peace process, future moves to reactivate peace-making. But
the talks were postponed until Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
However, his lieutenants, chief negotiator Saeb Eraket and
State Minister for International Cooperation Nabil Shaath held
talks with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Their detailed consultations on the related issues will be
referred to Mubarak and Arafat before they meet, according to
Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Shaath told reporters that the Palestinians
are still thoroughly examining the European call for delaying the
statehood declaration.
</P>
<P>
But he said May 4 is still the date fixed for the declaration,
and dismissed speculation that a postponement is imminent.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt is assisting the Palestinians with regard to
statehood declaration and is working with France to formulate a
unified Euro-Arab stand.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will meet U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington on
March 23 to explain the Palestinian viewpoints, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
