<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Removes Over 50,000 Land Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's Minister for Foreign
Affairs and Co-operation, Leonardo Simao, said here Monday that
the country has removed more than 50,000 land mines since peace
was achieved in October 1992.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of the parliament, Simao said the mine
clearance operation has cost more than 116 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The operation has been carried out in 10,560 square kilometers
of land area, 7,718 kilometers of highways, 90 kilometers of
railway lines and under 1, 825 kilometers of electricity
transmission lines.
</P>
<P>
By 1992, he said, an estimated two million land mines had been
planted in the southern African country during 16 years of war
between the government and the Renamo, a guerrilla force.
</P>
</TEXT>
