<HEADLINE> Burundi Warring Parties Seek to Build Trust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Burundi's warring parties
met again Monday at a seminar in Tanzania's northern town of
Arusha in an effort to build trust necessary to a national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Arusha said that representatives from Burundi's 18
parties, religious leaders, civil societies and women groups
discussed ways to achieve an amicable political solution to the
endless bloody conflicts.
</P>
<P>
They were also given advice by the former Finnish Prime
Minister Harri Holkeri and the ex-Foreign Minister of Bosnia
Muhamed Sacirbey on trust build-up.
</P>
<P>
The two told the participants, including the international
peace facilitator, Julius Nyerere, a former Tanzanian president,
that no degree of peace process can succeed until some degree of
trust is restored.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody benefits more than the other side. Violence complicates
further the abnormal situation," Sacirbey said, citing the example
of his own country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the four committees appointed to make
recommendations to restore democracy in Burundi also resumed their
meeting Monday in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
They continued to explore the nature of Burundi conflict,
democracy and good governance, peace and security and
reconstruction and economic development at the two-day seminar.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere has expressed his hope to reach a peace agreement at
least by June when the fifth round of Burundi peace talks is
scheduled to start.
</P>
<P>
He also stated that international community is ready to assist
Burundi in the reconstruction and to come to its feet again when
the rival factions reach a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
On January 23, the Great Lakes Region countries suspended the
economic sanctions, which were imposed on Burundi shortly after
Major Pierre Buyoya took power in a military coup in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
The suspension decision is to encourage the progress achieved
in the four rounds of talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
