<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The leading European stock markets
were slightly muted in trading Monday as a weak start on Wall
Street and an uneasy waiting for the UK's Budget on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of blue chips at the close was up 3.3
points at 6208.8. "Investors aren't willing to take significant
positions ahead of the Budget," said one dealer.
</P>
<P>
A weak start on Wall Street, which failed to extend the record
highs achieved last week, also hit London prices.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to remain subdued until after Chancellor
Gordon Brown has delivered his budget package on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts at HSBC Markets note that the healthy state of the
public finances mean that Brown could find room for a significant
fiscal easing, but "the political pressures for a giveway are
weak".
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the Xetra Dax closed down 1.02 percent at
4791.43. Share prices fell back after Wall Street moved lower in
early trading.
</P>
<P>
"The German market is lacking in self-confidence," a trader
said. However, telecommunications news had a strong effect on
share prices in both telecom and utilities sectors.
</P>
<P>
Shares of Deutsche Telekom and Deutsche Bank fell amid a row
over the bank's offer to buy Deutsche Telekom's cable television
business.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 finished 13.59 lower at 4175.97. French
stocks prices finish little changed as Wall Street failed to offer
support, but shares did improve from earlier lows.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 had hit a 4148.69 low, in response to comments by
Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn that the French economy
will expand by less than 2.7 percent in 1999, traders said.
</P>
