<HEADLINE> Top legislator on Constitutional Amendments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Top Chinese law maker Li Peng
today talked about the importance of amending the Chinese
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"Amending the Constitution this time aims to enshrine in the
country's fundamental law Deng Xiaoping theory as the nation's
guiding principle, the basic principle of running the country
according to law, and non-publicly-owned economic elements as an
important part of the national economy," he said. "This is a
requirement made necessary by changed realities."
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress, the nation's top lawmaking body, expressed the views at
a group discussion attended by Zhejiang deputies to the NPC, in
session here since last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the constitutional amendments this time around have
an important and far-reaching significance for building socialism
with Chinese characteristics," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng said that the enactment of a unified, comprehensive
contract law is conducive to standardizing market activities,
solving timely and correctly contract-related disputes, protecting
the legitimate rights and interests of parties involved, and
safeguarding economic order.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng expressed the hope that Zhejiang deputies would offer
views and suggestions on the draft contract law since the province
is noted for a well-developed market economy.
</P>
<P>
Li pointed out that running the country according to law and
building socialism on the basis of the rule of law is the Party's
basic principle in leading the people in managing state affairs.
Strengthening Party leadership is in agreement with bringing into
full play the role of the NPC, he said,
</P>
<P>
It is the role of the NPC and its Standing Committee to
enshrine in laws Party's policies and propositions that have
proven feasible, effective and reflective of people's will, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Has No Sincerity for Negotiation: Tibetan NPC Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A Tibetan legislator said here
today that the Dalai Lama has always been engaged in activities of
splitting the motherland since he fled abroad in the late 1950s,
and that he has no sincerity at all for holding negotiations with
the central government.
</P>
<P>
"No sovereign state in the world would allow any groups or
individuals to break the law and attempt to split the country.
What Dalai did was just intended to cause ethnic separation and
ruin the unity of the motherland," said Raidi, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the Tibet Autonomous Regional People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Raidi is here attending the ongoing Second Session of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
Raidi said that for a long period of time, the Dalai Lama had
claimed he was willing to start negotiations at one time and said
at another time he wouldn't accept it. On some occasions he even
lied to the world that the central government refused to hold
negotiations with him.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, he has never really wanted to start negotiations with
the central government, and has instead become the tool of some
foreign anti-China forces," Raidi said, adding that "His attitude
changes in pace with theirs, and the fundamental reason lies in
his desire to separate Tibet from China."
</P>
<P>
He said that the central government has repeatedly made clear
its attitude toward negotiations with the Dalai Lama, which is
that the latter must first stop his splittist activities, give up
any attempt to seek "Tibet independence", and acknowledge that
Tibet is an inalienable part of the Chinese territory, Taiwan is
one of China's provinces and that the government of the People's
Republic of China is the sole legitimate government representing
the whole China.
</P>
<P>
"On this basis, the central government has always kept the door
open for negotiations with the Dalai Lama, which can start at any
time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Raidi went on to point to the fact that the Dalai Lama was
formerly the chief boss for the feudal serfdom in old Tibet, and
that he had oppressed the Tibetan people with cruelty and done
them no good throughout his reign.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that over the past four decades since the
Democratic Reform was carried out and the feudal serfdom abolished
in Tibet, the Tibetan people have become masters of their own
destiny and have achieved tremendous successes in promoting
economic and social development in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"Hadn't there been disturbances and sabotage from Dalai, Tibet
would have achieved more rapid economic growth and greater social
progress," Raidi said.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan legislator also criticized some western people for
making irresponsible comments on Tibet while having no idea at all
of the region's history and current situation.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, it is also necessary for the Tibet Autonomous
Region to make more exchanges with the outside world, so as to
help more people to understand the actual situation in Tibet," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
