<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Recognized as Second Cheapest Property Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has become the second
cheapest property stock market behind Japan, according to Solomon
Smith Barney's new global comparative real estate research report.
</P>
<P>
The report notes, however, that on a discount to net asset
value (NAV) basis, Hong Kong appears more expensive with the stock
market's real estate sector trading at a 12.3 percent average
discount, while the rest of Asia, at a 25 to 40 percent discount
is beginning to look attractive to global investors. This compares
with a U.S. average discount of four percent, Australia at a 31
percent premium, and Continental Europe at a 15 to 20 discount to
NAV.
</P>
<P>
Solomon Smith Barney is a global, full-service investment
banking and securities brokerage firm with more than 514 offices
in 26 countries worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
