<HEADLINE> Solana Threatens Airstrike on Serbia if Peace Agreement Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana said on Tuesday that the military alliance is ready to
launch air strikes against Serbia if Yugoslavia does not accept an
autonomy plan for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
If Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic does not sign the
agreement, initiated by Western countries and including a NATO-
led peace implementation force, military options would be used,
Solana told a conference held in London to mark the 50th
anniversary of NATO.
</P>
<P>
All 16 NATO states agreed last October that military action
against Serbia would be legitimate and none of them have changed
their minds since, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed at the same time that no NATO nation supported
sending ground troops to fight their way into the southern Serbian
province.
</P>
<P>
Solana said NATO needed to develop a more comprehensive
political and economic strategy for southeastern Europe rather
than just deal piecemeal with the conflicts in Kosovo or wherever
the next problem flared.
</P>
<P>
"What we hope is that the start of Kosovo peace implementation
should be the start of a wider initiative to pull all parts of the
Balkans toward Europe, politically as well as economically," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Without such a comprehensive approach, we will never get
beyond treating the symptoms," said the secretary general.
</P>
