<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Researchers Uncover Genetic Link for Diabetes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Canadian researchers have found
that a "thrifty" gene, or genes, may account for the world's third
highest rate of diabetes in the Ojibway-Cree native reserve at
Sandy Lake in Northern Ontario province of Canada, the Globe and
Mail newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the University of Western Ontario and the
University of Toronto have been scouring the DNA of the Sandy Lake
natives for four years to find the genetic link.
</P>
<P>
The project, which was an unusual collaboration between
researchers and a native community, is believed to be among the
first to pinpoint a gene linked to diabetes in aboriginal people
who generally battle a greater incidence of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Robert Hegele, the geneticist working on the project, assumed
that Ojibway-Cree had a "thrifty" gene, or genes, that served them
well when they lived as nomadic tribal people.
</P>
<P>
"The theory is that an individual who had these genes had a
super-economic metabolic process," Dr. Hegele said.
</P>
<P>
Their bodies may have been genetically programmed to store
every calorie they ate to survive the lean times between hunts, he
said. But with satellite television, heated cottages and fast
foods on the reservation, there are no lean times. In the Ojibway-
Cree native reserve, which was built in the early 1990s amid dense
woods, its diabetes rate is five times the national average,
affecting 25 percent of the 2,000 residents. The rate jumps to
more than 50 percent among those over the age of 50 and early
signs of the disease can be detected in children as young as 10.
</P>
<P>
In many cases, diabetes has been so severe it has resulted in
limb amputations, blindness or kidney failure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Records Per Capita GDP Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, achieved a 1998 gross domestic product
(GDP) of 184.4 billion yuan (22 billion US dollars), up 13 percent
on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The Statistical Bulletin on 1998 Economic and Social
Development in Guangzhou shows that the city's per capita GDP of
27,500 yuan (3,323 US dollars) leads the list of 10 major Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin released today lists the growth rate for
agriculture at 4.1 percent, industry at 12.9 percent and service
sector at 14.1 percent. The service sector's GDP accounted for
more than half of the provincial total.
</P>
<P>
Economic development has led to rising income levels for
Guangzhou residents, with the per capita urban income level rising
by 13 percent on 1997 to 11,256 yuan. The per capita rural income
level grew 3.59 percent on 1997 to 5,629 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also indicate a general increase in living space for
both urban and rural residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
