<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers, Advisors on Governing China According to Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese legislators and government
advisors today described the endorsement of the principle of "
governing the country according to law" as "a milestone event" in
China's social advancement, which they believe will have a
profound impact on the country's modernization process in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
A draft amendment to China's Constitution submitted this
morning to the ongoing full session of the Chinese legislature,
the National People's Congress (NPC), for deliberation suggests
adding the following statement to the Constitution: The People's
Republic of China endorses the principle of "governing the country
according to law" and strives to build a socialist country based
on the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
"This revision will provide a legal guarantee for China's
current development strategy," said Wang Youhui, a member of the
Standing Committee of the Ninth NPC.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xi, a professor with the Law School of central China's
Wuhan University, noted that China is one of the world's few
countries which have an extremely long history of a feudal society.
</P>
<P>
"Promoting the rule of law is the most powerful weapon for
combating the remainder of feudalistic ideas, including the idea
of the rule by man," said Wang, a member of the Ninth National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), China's top advisory body also in session here
since last week.
</P>
<P>
China has greatly improved its legal system since it started
the reform and opening-up drive in 1978. Over the past two decades,
the NPC and its Standing Committee have enacted a total of 348
laws and relevant decisions.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China made three comprehensive revisions to its
Constitution, while the existing Constitution adopted in 1982 also
underwent two partial amendments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Bubbles Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar bubbled
higher Tuesday encouraged by gains in a leading commodity index,
an improved gold price and a stronger Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
"It's gained a bit of ground in the past 24 hours," Colonial
State Bank treasury manager Nick Volanakis said.
</P>
<P>
"It looks quite comfortable and a little stronger."
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading the Australian dollar was at 63.16 U.S.
cents, from 62.75 Monday.
</P>
<P>
Volanakis said the three main factors supporting the local unit
were the gains in gold and the Commodity Research Bureau (CRB)
index, as well as a stronger yen against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The CRB is an index of 17 U.S. futures markets and although not
weighted to Australia's exports, traders follow it as an indicator
for the commodity price-sensitive Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The CRB finished Monday night in New York up 1.11 at 187.64
points.
</P>
<P>
And gold for current delivery closed at 292.70 U.S. dollars per
ounce, up 3.20 U.S. dollars from Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading the Australian dollar was buying 76.29
Japanese yen, from 76.56 yen Previously.
</P>
<P>
Volanakis said there was a chance the Australian dollar could
head toward the 63.50 U.S. cents area Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There seems to be sellers between 63.20 U.S. cents and 63.25
at the moment, but if it can get through there it might squeeze up
towards 63.50," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also at the close here the Australian dollar was buying 0.5787
euro from 0.5792. 
</P>
</TEXT>
