<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Against Internationalizing Khmer Rouge Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen said Tuesday that he is against internationalizing the Khmer
Rouge issue which is Cambodia's "internal affairs."
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen made the remarks during a nearly four-hour exclusive
interview with French TV-5 Tuesday at his Takhmau residence.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the Khmer Rouge issue is
Cambodia's internal affairs and no foreign country should
interfere in it. Otherwise, Cambodia will lose its sovereignty and
the issue can never be resolved, he reiterated.
</P>
<P>
"According to Article 33 of our constitution, Khmer citizens
cannot be deprived of the nationality, and transferred to a
foreign country to be tried," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that it is necessary to prevent some foreign
countries from using the Khmer Rouge issue as an excuse to
intervene in Cambodia's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The capture of Ta Mok, the last Khmer Rouge leader still alive
who had not defected to the government, last weekend has
intensified the debate on setting up an international tribunal to
try the Khmer Rouge leaders.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Cambodian Foreign
Minister Hor Nam Hong this week will discuss a recent report by
three U.N. legal experts on the best options for trying Khmer
Rouge leaders.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen wants to try Ta Mok in a Cambodian court, instead of an
international tribunal, and he has already requested the Ministry
of Justice to discuss with courts to decide the procedure of
trial.
</P>
<P>
"Ta Mok is a Khmer criminal, the victims are Khmer and the
crimes he committed also occurred in Khmer soil so the tribunal
must be proceeded in Cambodia," Hun Sen told French TV in the
interview which was later broadcast by television Bayon.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, Hun Sen showed a video of Ta Mok filmed
during his interrogation in the military prosecutor's prison in
Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's Military Court has started from Tuesday to
investigate the charges of Ta Mok who was arrested Saturday in
Cambodia-Thai border. Ta Mok was charged by the prosecutor under
the law outlawing the Khmer Rouge which was adopted by the
National Assembly in 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to Article 4 of the law, "members of the political
body and military forces of the Khmer Rouge group or any one who
committed acts of conducting secession, destroying the royal
government...shall be deemed as criminals against internal
security, and sentenced to a term of 20 to 30 years in prison or
to a life imprisonment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
