<HEADLINE> Seoul, Washington to Continue "Sunshine Policy" Toward DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and the United States
Tuesday agreed to continue President Kim Dae-jung's "sunshine
policy" toward the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK),
which seeks reconciliation, exchange and cooperation based on
separating economics from politics.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to "solve the DPRK's nuclear and missile
issue within the framework of Seoul's engagement policy," said
South Korean Minister of Foreign Affairs Hong Soon-young.
</P>
<P>
"There was no change in U.S. support for President Kim Dae-jung'
s engagement policy," said Hong, after meeting with William Perry,
U.S. coordinator on DPRK policy, who arrived here Monday for a two-
day visit.
</P>
<P>
The two nations also reached an agreement on counter measures
if Pyongyang failed to respond favorably to the "sunshine policy".
</P>
<P>
Hong said the United States needs to be cautious in working out
counter measures if Seoul's engagement policy towards Pyongyang
fails.
</P>
<P>
"Neither over-reaction nor under-reaction (to DPRK) is
appropriate," Hong said.
</P>
<P>
Hong's remarks reflected mounting concerns that the United
States is different from South Korea in how to deal with Pyongyang
if the country refuses to accept the "sunshine policy."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is now pressed by the U.S. Congress
to take a harder stance against the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
South Korea urged the United States to pursue the current
engagement policy with patience and consistence.
</P>
<P>
Surgical strikes (against the DPRK) should not even be
considered, and any war on the Korean Peninsula is a life-or-death
matter for tens of thousands of Koreans as well as 37,000 U.S.
troops stationed here, said Hong.
</P>
<P>
"Our ultimate goal is peaceful co-existence (between South and
North)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Perry, former U.S. defense secretary, updated his draft report
on U.S. policy on the DPRK to South Korean officials and is
scheduled to submit his final report to President Clinton by the
end of this month.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Hong and other Korean leaders, the former U.
S. defense secretary met President Kim.
</P>
<P>
President Kim and Perry agreed that Seoul and Washington will
continue conferring with each other until Perry finishes his
review of the DPRK policy, said Presidential spokesman Park Jie-
won.
</P>
<P>
Perry left here for Japan Tuesday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
