<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily on Democratic Reforms in Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- "People's Daily" will carry an
editorial in its overseas edition Wednesday on the 40th
anniversary of democratic reforms in Tibet that reads as follows:
</P>
<P>
This year is the 40th anniversary of the democratic reform and
abolition of the feudal serfdom under the despotic theocratic rule
in Tibet. Forty years ago, on March 10, the upper class
reactionary clique representing the three categories of feudal
lords in Tibet launched an armed rebellion to maintain serfdom,
backed by imperialists and anti-Chinese forces in the
international community.
</P>
<P>
They tore up the "17-Article Agreement", declared Tibetan
independence, persecuted patriots, and began an all-round attack
on People's Liberation Army (PLA) forces stationed in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
But, with strong support from local people, the PLA soon put
down the rebellion and Dalai Lama and members of his group fled
abroad in panic.
</P>
<P>
In July that year, a massive movement of democratic reforms
swept over the plateau area, and the extremely backward and
reactionary system of serfdom under the despotic religious and
political rule was abolished. A million serfs suffering under
slavery who had been trampled on for generations stood up and
became master of their own fate, and a new historical period began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily on Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The three categories of feudal lords before Tibet's democratic
reform were administrative officials, the nobility, and high-
ranking lamas, who made up less than five percent of the
population but owned all the farmland, pastures, forests,
mountains, rivers, and most livestock.
</P>
<P>
Serfs and slaves made up more than 95 percent of the population
and had no land or personal freedom. Their owners had them at
their disposal because they were private property. They could
trade or sell them or present them as gifts.
</P>
<P>
The "13-Article Code" and "16-Article Code", which were in
effect for several hundred years in old Tibet, divided people into
three classes and nine ranks and people at the bottom of this
class system were worth a "straw rope". With the help of the law,
the serf-owners applied extremely cruel penalties like gouging out
eyes, cutting off feet, tongue, or hands, throwing people off
cliffs or into water, or executing them to maintain their rule.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan society before the democratic reform was darker and
more cruel than Europe's system of serfdom in the Middle Ages and
can be said to have been one of the world's most serious
violations of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The peaceful liberation of Tibet in 1951 brought hope to the
Tibetan people in their struggle for equal rights and economic
status. Tibetans craved reforms of the old system and many open-
minded people came to see that Tibet could never prosper without
reform.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the Tibetans' aspiration for reforms and
the history and actual situation of Tibet, the central people's
government took a very prudent attitude toward social reforms in
Tibet, and the "17-Article Agreement" on the peaceful liberation
of Tibet signed in May 1951 between the central government and the
local government in Tibet clearly states that reforms would be
carried out by the local government and not be forcefully
implemented by the central government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Jobless Rate Rises in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Germany's unemployment figures in
February rose by nearly 10,000 to 4.46 million with the jobless
rate hitting 11.6 percent, the Nuremberg-based German Federal
Labor Office reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure was 354,500 less than the same period last year, the
office said, adding that in seasonally adjusted terms,
unemployment in February was 4.076 million, 6,000 fewer than in
January.
</P>
<P>
In Germany's western states, 3.02 million people were
unemployed, 2,200 less than in January. In eastern Germany, the
number climbed by 12,000 to 1,442,000. The jobless rates were 9.7
percent and 19.1 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Bernhard Jagoda, president of the labor office, attributed the
depression in the job market to cold weather in February, and
indicated it was too early to read a trend into the market data.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
