<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Formulation, Revisions of China's Constitution (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- China's Constitution is the
fundamental law of the state, it has the supreme legal
authenticity, and is the basis for formulating all other laws. No
law or regulation should contravene the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of New China, the first Constitution of the
People's Republic of China was adopted by the First National
People's Congress in 1954, and the Constitution was twice
completely revised in 1975 and 1978.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, the Constitution was completely revised on the basis
of the 1954 version, and in 1988 and 1993, the Constitution was
twice partially revised.
</P>
<P>
The current Constitution stipulates the political and economic
systems of the country, the rights and obligations of the citizens,
the setup and the scope of responsibilities of the state organs,
and the fundamental tasks for the state in future.
</P>
<P>
Besides the preamble, the Constitution consists of 138 articles
in four chapters.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the revision of the Constitution, Article 64 of the
Constitution stipulates: "Amendments to the Constitution are to be
proposed by the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress or by more than one-fifth of the deputies to the National
People's Congress and adopted by a majority vote of more than two-
thirds of all the deputies to the Congress."
</P>
<P>
The Constitution is the legalization of the democratic system
in China and the general regulations for the organization and
activities of the state and is the country's own base and core for
its legalization. Therefore, the stipulation on the method for the
revision of the Constitution must take the stability of the
Constitution into consideration.
</P>
<P>
In China, the revision of the Constitution may be conducted in
the form of adopting amendments to the Constitution, such as the
amendments made in 1988 and 1993, as well as the form of rewriting,
such as the Constitutions adopted in 1975, 1978 and 1982 which
were completely rewritten on the basis of the former ones.
</P>
<P>
The 1954 Constitution was drafted on the basis of "The Common
Program of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference".
The draft sought wide-ranging deliberations among the Chinese
people and on September 20, 1954, it was adopted at the First
Session of the First National People's Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Further Development in China-Ukraine Trade Relations Noted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese State Councilor Wu
Yi said here Tuesday that there's much to be done to promote
economic cooperation between China and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the remark during her meeting with Sergei Tigipko,
Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister in charge of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The two sides expressed their concern over the decline in trade
volume between the two countries in recent years. Wu said that the
two governments should play a stronger role in promoting bilateral
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation should be diversified and focused on the
processing and manufacturing industries, she added.
</P>
<P>
Tigipko said the Ukrainian government will encourage more
Chinese investment by helping the existing cooperation projects
run more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China is one of the largest trade partners
of Ukraine and the promotion of bilateral economic cooperation has
a broad prospect and bright future.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, China agreed to donate 5 million yuan (about
604 thousand U.S. dollars) to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Wu arrived in Kiev on Monday afternoon for a four-day visit.
She has already visited Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Belarus.
</P>
</TEXT>
