<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Formulation, Revisions of China's Constitution (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This Constitution established the fundamental political system
for New China and stipulated, for the first time, "All power in
the People's Republic of China belongs to the people."
</P>
<P>
The 1975 Constitution was formulated during the "Cultural
Revolution" and it had lots of pitfalls in its guiding ideology
and concrete regulations.
</P>
<P>
This Constitution adopted in March 1978 had greater changes
compared with the 1975 Constitution and restored the systems of
open trial, defending and procuratorates. Since it was promulgated
before the Third Plenum of the 11th Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), the 1978 version of the
Constitution still had many shortcomings, such as the erroneous
wording "Persisting in continuous revolution under the
dictatorship of the proletariat."
</P>
<P>
The 1982 Constitution was revised based on nationwide
discussions. It inherited and developed the basic principles of
the 1954 Constitution, summed up the experience of the socialist
development in China and absorbed international experience. This
Constitution is a fundamental law with Chinese characteristics
that meets the needs of China's socialist modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
It stipulates that China takes the four cardinal principles --
socialist road, people's democratic dictatorship, leadership of
the Communist Party and Marxism-Leninism and Mao Zedong Thought --
as guidelines and it stresses that the basic task for the nation
is to concentrate its effort on socialist modernization drive. In
developing socialist democracy, it stipulates that all citizens
are equal before the law, no organization nor person has the
privilege of overstepping the bounds of the law. It also
stipulates that the state leaders must serve no more than two
consecutive terms (10 years), and this actually abolishes the de
facto life term of leading officials.
</P>
<P>
The First Session of the Seventh NPC in 1988 approved
amendments to Article 11 of Constitution: "The state permits
private economy to exist and grow within the limits prescribed by
law" and non-public economy is "a complement to the socialist
public economy."
</P>
<P>
The First Session of the Eighth NPC made nine amendments to the
Constitution and added into the Constitution the theory of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics, adhering to the
reform, opening up and the multi-party cooperation under the
leadership of the CPC and the political consultation system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
