<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Secretary Arrives in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen arrived here Tuesday on a two-day visit for talks
with Kuwaiti officials on military cooperation and regional
security.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is scheduled to meet with Kuwaiti Emir Jaber Al-Ahmed
Al-Sabah, Crown Prince and Prime Minister Saad Al-Abdullah
Al-Salem Al-Sabah and Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Defense Salem Sabah Al-Salem Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is the sixth leg of Cohen's current nine-nation Mideast
tour, which has taken him to Bahrain, Saudi Arabia, Oman, the
United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar. His tour also includes stops in
Egypt, Jordan and Israel.
</P>
<P>
During his whirlwind visit in the Gulf region, Cohen has
announced Washington's approval to sell the AMRAAM air-to-air
missiles to Bahrain, Saudi Arabia and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the clashes between Iraq's defenses and the
U.S.-British warplanes enforcing the no-fly zones in northern and
southern Iraq, Cohen stressed Sunday in Saudi capital Riyadh that
air strikes against Iraq must "continue as long as Baghdad defies
the no-fly zones."
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones following
the 1991 Gulf War triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also said that the U.S. forces stationed in Saudi Arabia
will step up joint military exercises with Saudi army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
