<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Files Libel Suit Against Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
filed Tuesday afternoon a 100 million peso (2.5 million U.S.
dollars) libel suit against the Manila Times for its story
published last month linking him to an alleged rigging of a 17
billion peso government contract.
</P>
<P>
In an affidavit-complaint filed before the Office of the
Prosecutor in Mandaluyong City, Manila, Estrada said that the
story, which contained "libelous comments and conclusions," is an
open attack and serious affront on his "reputation, honor and
dignity" as a person as well as his "honesty and integrity as a
public official."
</P>
<P>
Estrada also sought exemplary damages of at least 1 million
peso from the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with reporters following the filing of the
libel complaint, Estrada said that should the case prosper, he
would donate the amount to an orphanage or to his administration's
scholarship program to send 100 Muslim youths abroad each year to
pursue higher academic studies.
</P>
<P>
Named as respondents in the case were Robina Gokongwei-Pe, of
Metromedia Times Corp., mother firm of The Manila Times; Liberato
Gomez Jr., Lisa Gokongwei, Marcia Gokongwei, Rhodora Dakanay and
Pedro Juanitas.
</P>
<P>
Gokongwei-Pe is the president and director of Metromedia Times
Corp., while Gomez, Lisa and Marcia Gokongwei are directors of the
corporation.
</P>
<P>
Dakanay is a director and treasurer of the corporation, while
Juanitas is a director and corporate secretary of the corporation.
</P>
<P>
The complaint also listed as respondents Manila Times publisher
Ermin Garcia Jr., Editor-in-Chief Ma. Lourdes Mangahas, Managing
Editor Chit Estella, News Editor Glenda Gloria and Chief of
Business Reporters Joel Gaborni.
</P>
<P>
The president presented as evidence a clipping from the
February 16, 1999 issue of the paper, whose banner story read,
"Palace in P17 billion contract rigging, President was unwitting
ninong (sponsor)."
</P>
<P>
"A reading of the headline and my picture immediately conveys
the thinking that I am a party and/or that I have participated in
the contract rigging referred to in the subject headline, and I
gave my go-signal to such rigging, which is far from the truth,"
he said in his complaint.
</P>
<P>
With the filing of the libel case, Estrada became the second
president since former president Corazon C. Aquino to file a libel
suit against a newspaper during the presidential incumbency.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, Mrs. Aquino filed a libel case against the late
journalist Luis Beltran for writing in his column that she hid
under the bed at the height of a coup attempt in December 1989.
The case was dismissed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
