<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down on Concern Over US Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
drifted slightly lower Tuesday in anticipation of a softer night
on Wall Street, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries shed 8.8 points to 2920.8, sliding
from an intra-day peak of 2935.1 points.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index retreated 11.8 points to 5290.8. The
all resources surrendered 7.4 points to 971.5, with copper prices
falling to near 12-year lows and diversified miner Rio Tinto going
ex-dividend contributing to the fall.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones adviser Stuart Smith said the Globex
futures on the S&AMP;P 500 finished marginally lower after being seven
points up at midday, indicating investors anticipated a fall on
U.S. markets Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
"There's an expectation that market will be down tonight,"
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
"That's caused a bit of non-confidence here this afternoon."
</P>
<P>
Among industrial stocks on the local bourse, Telstra was the
focus of early attention with the stock peaking at 8.93 Australian
dollars before drifting back to close three cents down at 8.73
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the stock was initially buoyed by expectations of
an improved half-year result due out this week and a growing
belief that the Senate would not pass the planned sell-off of the
remainder of the telco giant.
</P>
<P>
Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus fell three cents, AAPT remained steady
at 4.30 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bank index retreated 12.8 points to 6797.0, with National
Australia Bank the only "Big 4" player to finish in positive
territory, adding 10.4 cents.
</P>
<P>
Westpac fell 15 cents, ANZ shed 1.7 cents, and Commonwealth
Bank eased two cents.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the industrial sector, Qantas added five cents and
Leighton Holdings shot up eight cents after announcing it had won
a housing development contract in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The gold index gained 9.7 points to 1028.1 on the strength of a
rise in precious metal prices.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold bullion in Sydney was 292.25 U.S. dollars per
ounce, compared to a close of 288.45 Monday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 326.3 million stocks traded for 1.02
billion Australian dollars (642.6 million U.S. dollars), with
falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks by 658 to 496 and 469
stocks remaining steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
