<HEADLINE> Philippine Army Launches Operations Against Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine army troops Tuesday
launched a massive combat operation against New People's Army
(NPA) rebels who raided an army detachment, abducted a soldier and
carted away 12 pieces of high-powered firearms last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Maj. Gen. Santos Gabison, commander of the army's 4th Infantry
Division based in Cagayan de Oro, said the raid was well planned
in which the NPA rebels posed as residents of Lianga, Surigao del
Sur and invited soldiers manning the Army detachment to attend a
wedding feast.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the soldiers and civilian militiamen left their
post, 60 fully armed NPA rebels raided the detachment and captured
detachment commander Alvio Lozada.
</P>
<P>
The rebels also took away 12 pieces of high-powered firearms
which included seven M-14s, two Garands, two Carbine and one M-16.
</P>
<P>
Lozada is the fourth officer kidnapped by the rebels since
February 17. Still being held by the rebels are Brig. Gen. Victor
Obillo, Capt. Eduardo Montealto and Police Chief Inspector
Roberto.
</P>
<P>
The government has demanded for the release of the captives
pending resumption of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
NPA rebels suffered a series of major setbacks during the past
13 years that reduced their combatants from a high of 25,600 to an
estimated 6,000 at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have been trying to rebuild their forces since last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
