<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Robbers Get Away With Millions of Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- An armored security van carrying
at least 2.5 million Australian dollars (1.5 million U.S. dollars)
was spirited away early Tuesday by four armed bandits in eastern
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The only witness to the daring heist was driver Matthew Kelly,
who was found handcuffed but unharmed in the back of the van in
the south of Brisbane, capital city of Queensland state, the
Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Kelly, 30, told police that four people dressed in black and
wearing white gloves hijacked the Brinks Australia vehicle as it
made its final pickup from the Sunnybank Hills Shopping Plaza on
the city's southside at 2:00 a.m.
</P>
<P>
At least two of the robbers were armed with rifles when they
apparently overpowered him as he waited inside the vehicle with
the motor running while two other security guards went inside to
collect the day's taking.
</P>
<P>
The van was found seven hours later abandoned behind the
Calamvale Recreation Center with Kelly locked inside, handcuffed
to a door handle but otherwise unharmed.
</P>
<P>
Despite his ordeal, police took Kelly back to the scene Tuesday
afternoon and spent several hours interviewing him in the hope of
uncovering a clue that would help them crack the case.
</P>
<P>
Detective Inspector Peter Scanlon said Kelly, who have worked
for Brinks security for just two and a half months, had been
questioned extensively by detectives but could not give a detailed
description of his assailants.
</P>
<P>
"Even though police were at the scene within minutes we have
little to go on at this stage," he said.
</P>
<P>
There were no signs of forced entry to the armored van and
police were presuming Kelly was overpowered and forced to open up.
</P>
<P>
Police have set up checks at air, bus and train departure
stations in case the robbers dump their getaway car and try to
leave the city by public transport.
</P>
<P>
Forty policemen were immediately assigned to the investigation,
but Scanlon said there were no early leads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
