<HEADLINE> NATO Official: Paris Meeting on Kosovo Could be Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 9 (Xinhua) - The Kosovo peace meeting, due to
resume next Monday in Paris, could be delayed for a few days to
allow more time for progress, a senior NATO official said here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official, who asked not to be identified, said
international mediators wanted the Paris meeting to be a signing
ceremony for an agreement drafted at talks in Rambouillet last
month, with a few days of detailed discussion on implementation,
according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
Once Kosovo ethnic Albanians agree to sign, the mediators will
concentrate on winning Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
acceptance of the full package, including a NATO-led
implementation force which he has so far rejected. If they succeed
in making progress, the Paris conference could be postponed for a
few days to allow time to complete the negotiations, the NATO
official said.
</P>
<P>
"I think it won't be Monday," he was quoted as saying, and
added that the meeting could last "perhaps up to seven days."
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, NATO Secretary-general Javier Solana repeated
the threat to use force if necessary when addressing a conference
here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
