<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Urges India to Reduce Trade Imbalance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh asked India on Tuesday to
allow duty-free access of Bangladeshi products to Indian market to
narrow the huge trade imbalance between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The key solution for reducing the huge trade imbalance is to
allow Bangladeshi goods duty-free access to India on a
non-reciprocal basis,
</P>
<P>
The comment was made by Commerce and Industries Minister Tofail
Ahmed at a meeting here with his Indian counterpart, Ramakrishna
Hedge, who arrived here Tuesday on a three-day visit to
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's imports from India stood at 755 million dollars
during the 1997-98 fiscal year, while its exports to the latter
was 50 million dollars only.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed requested Hedge to take appropriate steps to reduce the
trade gap, which he said would help improve his country's trade
capacities and increase intra-SAARC (South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation) trade. The intra-regional trade now is only
about 3 percent of the total of all SAARC member countries.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to Bangladesh's liberalization in the early 90s, the
country's import from India have increased substantially and India
could do a lot for increasing Bangladesh's exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We want speedy implementation of the decisions so far taken to
expand regional trade," said Ahmed, complaining that the tariff,
concession and removal of non-tariff barriers granted to
Bangladesh by India in the last two years have largely remained
unimplemented.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that India import ready-made garments from
Bangladesh and Indian entrepreneurs set up joint-ventures in
Bangladesh with the products to be marketed in India on a buy-back
system.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the call for expanding import from Bangladesh,
the Indian minister said that India needs lots of goods to import
from Bangladesh. On the issue of expansion of regional and
sub-regional trade, he said, "We should made a joint campaign to
expand our bilateral and mutual trade."
</P>
<P>
He proposed to use Chittagong port in southeast Bangladesh for
goods destined for the north-eastern region of India.
</P>
<P>
In reply to Hedge's proposal of importing products of natural
gas from Bangladesh, Ahmed said the country's priority is to meet
the local demand of gas. "Definitely we will go for export if we
have surplus," he added.
</P>
<P>
At a luncheon meeting Tuesday, hosted by the Federation of
Bangladesh Chamber of Commerce and Industry, Hedge said it was now
the turn of Bangladesh to have a free trade agreement with India,
following Nepal and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"My idea is that the SAARC countries must come closer and
closer," and relations be strengthened to such an extent that all
members could adopt a common currency, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a week-long Indian trade fair began in the city on
Tuesday to promote exports to Bangladesh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
