<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Responds Positively To Export Market Challenges (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- China's increasing commercial
skills in adapting to turbulent market changes in the face of the
still rippling Asian financial crisis have been highlighted at the
East China Fair which opened here on March 5th.
</P>
<P>
Transactions and turnover in sales and contracts have totaled
330 million US dollars in the first four days of the annual fair,
slightly higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
"The result is much better than expected and indicates that
China is becoming increasingly used to adapting to international
market changes in foreign trade," said Zhou Hongli, deputy
director of the general office of the fair's organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
Chinese exports, which are often labor and resource intensive,
have been put at a competitive disadvantage on the world markets
by the growth of overseas products with a high added value and
high level of technical content, according to industry experts.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis has posed the greatest challenges to
China's foreign trade as massive currency devaluation in Thailand,
Malaysia, Indonesia, the Philippines, the Republic of Korea and
some other countries in Asia reduced the demand for Chinese
products while raising the export competitiveness of the crisis-
hit countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
To turn around this negative situation, China has intensified
its efforts to improve product quality, diversify export markets
and optimize its export mix, among other measures.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China's decision not to devalue its currency, the
yuan, has effectively helped to avoid domestic economic
instability and prevented a new round of currency devaluation in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
All these measures combined to enable China to realize a 0.5
percent increase in exports last year, which, though significantly
lower than the 20.9 percent in 1997, was in sharp contrast to
substantial export declines in other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Starting this year China has unveiled measures to reform its
foreign trade system, such as reducing the number of goods with
export permits from 115 to 59, empowering 61 private enterprises
to engage in foreign trade for the first time and allowing greater
flexibility in the administration of the export and import rights
of over 6,000 large industrial enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Responds Positively To Export Market Challenges (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In east Jiangsu Province, China's third largest export region,
efforts have been stepped up to tap the markets in Latin America
and Africa. Last year, Jiangsu's exports to Latin America and
Africa went up by more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
"This is important for us to retain market share," Dai Yongyin,
Deputy Director of Jiangsu Provincial Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation Committee, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Ningbo Youngor Group Co. Ltd., one of the best established
garment manufacturers in east Zhejiang Province, and also a major
exporter, has adopted a "brandname strategy" to increase exports.
At the fair, it exhibited a range of products in different styles
for customers in Europe, the United States, Australia, Africa, and
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
"We enjoy a brandname privilege and our market potential is
great so long as we can respond to market changes in a timely
manner," said Fang Jianming, one of the company's traders who was
holding an order from a German importer in his hand.
</P>
<P>
To prepare for the possibility of an even harder export
situation this year, China will continue to expand its experiments
in Sino-foreign trade joint ventures, strive to export directly to
overseas chainstores, encourage enterprises to set up plants
overseas, and increase financial support for the export of
machinery and electronics, according to Xu Bingjin, Assistant
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Import and Export Bank of China, a major vehicle for
financing exports, has upped its line of export credit to 35
billion yuan this year from 1998's 25.6 billion yuan, which can
only benefit exporters in the short term.
</P>
<P>
In the interest of long-term goals, China will also establish
export-oriented scientific and technological industrial parks and
use new and high technology to renovate traditional industries in
an effort to increase the technical content and competitiveness of
Chinese products, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that we can offset much of the adverse impact
of the turbulent world market and ensure a better development of
China's foreign trade," he said.
</P>
<P>
Many trade officials and exporters participating in the fair
say they have seen signs of a possible improvement in China's
export situation this year after the sudden plunge in growth from
1997's 20.9 percent to only 0.5 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji last week called for "all
possible means" to increase exports to help boost economic growth,
which reached 7.8 percent last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
