<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increasing Debt Becomes Threat to S.Korea's Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's debt is expected to
rise this year, posing a threat to the nation's efforts for an
early economic recovery, said the Korea Center for Free Enterprise
(CFE) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The center's report said many unpredictable factors in the
financial and industrial restructuring may push the government's
debt beyond 60 percent of the gross national product (GNP) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The remark is quite different from a government-issued forecast
which claims that its debt volume, including external debt
guarantees for domestic firms, will rise to 200 trillion won (some
180 billion U.S. dollars), or 45 percent of GNP, by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Bad loans at local banks may turn out to be far greater than
expected, and the government's attempt to quickly implement
industrial restructuring will further add to its fiscal burdens,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Should the massive fiscal support for financial and industrial
restructuring be simultaneously accompanied by a similar drive to
expand budgets for unemployment and pump-priming projects, the
government debt will easily exceed the 60-percent level of this
year's GNP, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also warned that heavy tax burdens stemming from
heavy debts could disrupt many economic activities.
</P>
<P>
"People will increasingly lose their taste for savings and
investments, and pay more attention to evading taxes. Moreover,
the government's ability to provide public services will be
affected," it said.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government's debt began surging in the wake of
the foreign exchange crisis in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
The debt stood at 12.1 percent of GNP as of the end of 1997,
which was considered exceptionally low compared with those of
Japan, the United States and other industrialized countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
