<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former French PM Acquitted in Blood Contamination Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Former French Prime Minister Laurent
Fabius and former Minister of Social Affairs Georgina Dufoix, who
stood a two-month trial for the 1985 contamination of government
blood stocks by AIDS, were acquitted on Tuesday by the Court of
Justice of the Republic.
</P>
<P>
Former Secretary of State of Health Edmond Herve was condemned
but would not serve jail sentence because he had not benefited
from the right of presumption of innocence during the judicial
investigation, said the court.
</P>
<P>
The three former ministers were accused of "involuntary
homicide and involuntary attack of physical integrity of persons"
by seven people who obtained AIDS through transfusion of the
contaminated blood.
</P>
<P>
The court said that taking into account of the lack of enough
knowledge about AIDS, the charges against Fabius and Dufoix did
not stand.
</P>
<P>
But the court said that Herve, 56, had failed to ordered the
verification of the blood products prior to August 1, 1985, the
date by which an AIDS checking system had been introduced.
</P>
<P>
He was also blamed for not informing the patients who had blood
transfusion at that time after the contamination was discovered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
