<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Worried Over Possible Price Drop of Diamond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has
expressed worries over the possible price drop of diamond on the
international market following decreasing needs, which might
affect the country's mineral industry, the main sources of
revenue.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Sumbula, Deputy Minister of Geology and Mines, has said
that the prices of diamond would sooner or later decline after the
reduced demand in the international market, following the
financial crisis in Asia and Latin America, the Angola Daily
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The price drop of diamond may pose as yet another disaster for
the country after the the oil price decline in the world market,
Sumbula said, adding that the government is getting about 600
million U.S. dollars from diamond a year, with some of the mines
controlled by the rebel National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The Geology and Mines Ministry declared at the beginning of the
year that the government controled mines turned out about two
million karat of diamond in 1998, worth about 450 million dollars,
while the informal sector produced about 100,000 karat, worth
about 200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Angola is also an important oil producer, next only to Nigeria
in Africa, with a daily production of about 780,000 barrels. The
sharp drop in oil price in the world market has greatly reduced
the country's foreign currency income, ushering in financial
crisis and price hike in the southern African country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
