<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Suffering From Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Precipitation from October to January was 50 percent less than
in normal years and the province's reservoirs had 6.4 billion cu.m.
of water in January, down 20 percent from the amount for the same
period of a normal year.
</P>
<P>
The drought has affected 300,000 ha. of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say that it comes from lingering sub-tropical
high pressure areas and less cold air from the north. High
temperatures are expected to continue this month, reducing the
possibility of precipitation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
