<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Close 2.62 Percent Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks closed 2.62
percent higher today with the Hang Seng Index surging 268.96
points to 10,532.95.
</P>
<P>
Local dealers attributed the sharp growth to continued buying
by institutional investors encouraged by the 1999/2000 financial
budget announced by the Hong Kong government last week.
</P>
<P>
The budget contained plans for a 13 billion HK dollar (1.6
billion U.S. dollar) Cyberport for high-tech industries, a
proposal to privatize the Mass Transit Railway Corp. and
revelation that the government was in negotiations with Disneyland
for a theme park in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
However, some profit-taking was seen in Hongkong Telecom shares,
which have appreciated sharply in the past week stimulated by a
cooperation project with American software giant Microsoft today.
Hongkong Telecom shares went down 20 HK cents at the close.
</P>
<P>
Today's market turnover was 5.622 billion HK dollars (721
million U.S. dollars), 215 million HK dollars (27 million U.S.
dollars) less than Monday's amount.
</P>
<P>
The share prices gained 47.5 points, or 0.46 percent, to open
at 10,311.49 Tuesday morning and closed 198.64 points, or 1.94
percent, higher at lunch break.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index went up 22.87 points, or 0.22 percent,
to close at 10,263.99 on Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
