<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Bank Loans Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The amount of loans extended by
South Korean domestic banks to enterprises rose 511.8 billion won
(some 412 million U.S. dollars last month from the previous month,
showing the first growth in seven months, the Bank of Korea said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the rise of bank loans to a surge
in discount of commercial papers for mid-size companies.
</P>
<P>
Demand for funds by households and mid-size companies have been
on a steady rise this month. Household loans rebounded by 140
billion won (112 million dollars) this month.
</P>
<P>
Bank loans to households and mid-size companies dropped by 1.71
trillion won (1.37 billion dollars) to 4.59 trillion won (3.69
billion dollars) in August-December period of 1998. In January,
the amount fell by 485.9 billion won (391 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
South Korean banks have spurred their lending to households and
the private sector by lowering interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
