<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Expresses Interest in HK Cyberport Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates
today expressed interest in participating in the planned Cyberport
project in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Gates, answering questions at a press conference here to
announce a cooperative project with Hongkong Telecom, said his
company will "participate in the Cyberport, making sure we put in
engineers and architects there so that all the companies have the
media access," he said.
</P>
<P>
Between now and the time when the Cyberport gets done,
Microsoft will "encourage local software activity," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Financial Secretary Donald Tsang announced the 13
billion HK dollar (1.7 billion U.S. dollar) Cyberport project in
his budget address on March 3.
</P>
<P>
Gates, who arrived here Monday for a three-day visit before
going to South China's Shenzhen, met with officials of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region this morning and "talked about
a number of initiatives they are taking."
</P>
<P>
"It's a signal that there is a great opportunity for
entrepreneurial businesses, the software businesses going to be a
very fast-growing business with a variety of different companies
coming into it. And I think it's important that Hong Kong
participates in that," Gates said.
</P>
<P>
Gates also attended an Asian Enterprise Summit along with 160
business executives to introduce his company's digital nervous
system.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Hong Kong's intention to build itself into a
telecommunications hub in Asia, Gates said some of the pieces in
the joint project launched by his company and Hongkong Telecom was
also serving Hong Kong's goal of becoming a hub for global trade.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that the only real high-tech centers in the world
today are no more than a few cities in the United States, Gates
said he is "fairly optimistic" that there is enough demand that
places like Malaysia, Singapore and Hong Kong can be successful in
being great software centers.
</P>
<P>
"...It's great to be taking the right steps to a position Hong
Kong is a leader there. It starts with education, and the second
thing is the high-speed communications network," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Telecom Chief Executive Linus W. L. Cheung, also
attending the press conference, said Hong Kong is very well
positioned to be a hub not only for communications but for data
and e-commerce by taking advantage of its bilingual portal.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong must transform from being over relying on one or two
sectors of the economy to an information society," he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
