<HEADLINE> Military Shake-up Begins in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A massive shake-up of the army, navy
and air force has begun in Nigeria with hundreds of military
officers being retired compulsorily, media reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the present reorganization process which began last week,
dozens of the officers of the army, navy and air force have handed
out their letters of disengagement from service.
</P>
<P>
A reliable source at the military headquarters in Lagos told
the Post Express that those affected in the army started receiving
their letters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The source disclosed that the disengagement exercise cuts
across all ranks and affects mainly those that have had
disciplinary cases.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 senior military officers from the rank of
lieutenant-colonel and above have been retired compulsorily, The
Punch newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On the list, the paper said, were 125 army officers including
two major generals and four brigadiers general, 91 senior navy
officers including one vice admiral and 84 air force officers
including one air vice marshal.
</P>
<P>
Affected officers from both the Nigerian army and air force
were said to have been served their letters of retirement last
week.
</P>
<P>
The three services also gave some of the senior officers who
have served for 35 years the option of formally resigning from
service, the paper quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
A senior army officer said the exercise was being carried out
simultaneously in the three services in the west African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
