<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's Trade with U.S. Still Abysmal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Africa remained a faint blip
on the United States' trade radar last year, despite its
much-touted desire to help integrate Africa into the global
economy, Business Day paper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 47 African states south of the Sahara bought 6.77 billion
U.S. dollars worth of goods from the United States, accounting for
a fraction under one percent of U.S. merchandise exports
worldwide, the U.S. commerce department statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The figures indicated an increase on 1997 of less than 0.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The region's exports to the United States, at 13.1 billion
dollars, represented only 1.4 percent of U.S. imports worldwide in
1998.
</P>
<P>
This was down from 1.9 percent a year earlier, mainly
reflecting the sharp drop in the oil price.
</P>
<P>
The United States said it has sourced a strategically
significant 26 percent of its oil imports, worth 7.6 billion U.S.
dollars, from Africa, principally Nigeria, Angola and Gabon, with
smaller quantities supplied by the two Congos and Equatorial
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
But for oil imports, the United States would have run a 1.3
billion dollars trade surplus with the region.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC), a 14-nation
bloc, received 65 percent of U.S. exports to Africa, valued at 4.4
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It was the source of 6.2 billion dollars of U.S. imports, or 47
percent of the goods the 47 countries sold to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Excluding oil, South Africa exported to the United States 56
percent of Africa's goods worth 5.4 billion dollars, and accounted
for 54 percent of the region's total imports from the United
States, at 3.7 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
