<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Sink on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed weaker on
Singapore Stock Market Tuesday as poor banking results kept market
sentiment negative and the selling of bank stocks pulled the key
Straits Times Index down.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) lost 11.32 points to
close at 1,440.52 in thin trading.
</P>
<P>
The total volume was comparatively low at 138.35 million shares
worth 270.49 million Singapore dollars (156.17 million U.S.
dollars). Tuesday's session saw 87 counters ending higher, 133
lower and 207 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Wing T was the most active stock with 10.33 million shares
done. Also among the most heavily traded, JC MPH W00 closed on a
volume of 10.04 million shares and DBS Land finished on a volume
of 9.15 million stocks.
</P>
<P>
CityDev headed the top movers with a rise of 15 cents to 7.5
Singapore dollars. It was followed by Datacraft that picked up 11
cents to close at 2.29 U.S. dollars. SemMarLog was up 10 cents to
close at 3.4 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Elec&AMP;E led the descent of the day with a
plunge of 96 cents to finish at 4.54 Singapore dollars. It was
followed by SPH that retreated 50 cents to 20.5 Singapore dollars.
OCBC F and SPH 100 each sank 40 cents and ended at 11.6 and 20.5
Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said investors were discouraged by the poor results of
the Development Bank of Singapore whose bad loan provisions were
more than doubled to just under 1 billion Singapore dollars and
whose net profit halved to 222.7 million Singapore dollars in
1998.
</P>
<P>
A local broker was quoted as saying, "Banks have come off quite
a lot because of their poor results and the market may head for
more weakness."
</P>
<P>
However, brokers noted that the weakness was offset by the
buying in property counters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
