<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unity, Reconciliation Commission Set up in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
announced the formation of the National Unity and Reconciliation
Commission, sources from the Office of the President told the
Rwanda News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The current Minister of Public Service, Jean Nepomuscene
Nayinzira, from the Christian Democratic Party (PDC), was
appointed last Friday chairman. Other members include Rose
Mukankomeje, vice-chairman, and former Minister of Gender, Aloysia
Inyumba, who was appointed Secretary General.
</P>
<P>
Seven other people were also appointed.
</P>
<P>
Francois Gasana Ndoba, a human rights activist living in
Belgium was proposed as a candidate for the chairmanship of the
Human Rights Commission by the commission, to be elected president
of the Human Rights commission by parliament.
</P>
<P>
Both commissions were proposed by the Arusha peace accord of
August 4, 1993 between the then rebel Rwandan Patriotic Front
(RPF) and the Kigali regime, which unfortunately could not be
implemented because of the genocide of Tutsis which rocked the
country in April-July 1994.
</P>
<P>
After the genocide was stopped by RPF, the latter agreed with
other political forces which were not involved in the killings to
form a government of national unity, and maintained the plan to
set up both commissions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
