<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Since December 19, the day when the "Desert Fox" operation
ended, the U.S. Air Force made 3,224 sorties in the two no-fly
zones in Iraq where they fired 274 missiles and killed from 20 to
several dozen civilians. The bombings, which were aimed at
weakening the Iraqi regime, have so far proved inefficient in
destabilizing Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
-- Under the American pressure, the Kosovo Liberation Army has
announced its readiness to sign the plan on substantial autonomy
in Kosovo, but on condition that "the free expression of the will
of the Kosovo people is guaranteed at the end of a three-year
interim period." Meanwhile, the distrust of the Yugoslav
authorities toward NATO has gone deeper after the international
arbitrary authorities in Bosnia declared Brcko, which was
controlled by the Serbs, a "neutral" city.
</P>
<P>
Le Monde:
</P>
<P>
-- Jean-Arcady Meyer, a specialist of artificial intelligence
and director of the animal lab of the Paris VI University, said
that through observing animals, robots can use highly
sophisticated tools of men, but the human model is too complicated
for them to imitate.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami is due to begin on
Tuesday a three-day visit to Italy, the first of its kind by an
Iranian head of state to a country of the European Union since the
1979 Islamic Revolution. The visit, which is aimed at opening up
the Iranian diplomacy and restoring the international image of the
Islamic republic, precedes another one by Khatami to France on
April 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
