<HEADLINE> Changed Life of Former Tibetan Serf Owner (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Soinam Dorje, a former Tibetan serf
owner, has said that he did not complain when his vast farmland
and real estate were distributed among serfs 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"My life is more comfortable now than at that time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Soinam, 71, is a vice-chairman of the Prefectural Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference in Shannan
Prefecture of China's Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
He lives in a two-storey villa, which is two kilometers away
from his office, and goes to work in a Toyota sedan car provided
by the government. "I did not even know what a car looked like in
the old days," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Before Tibet's Democratic Reform in 1959, Soinam was a senior
official in the Shannan government and owned five manors, 45
hectares of farmland, 75 serfs, a three-storey house and vast
stretches of forest and grassland, with an annual income of 67,900
kg of grain as well as large amounts of meat and butter. This was
an income standing at middle level among the serf-owner class of
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"The Democratic Reform was a turning point in Tibet's history
and a great achievement in changing the structures of Tibet's serf
and serf-owner class and its economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the property of serf-owners, two ways were adopted
during the two-year Democratic Reform, namely, to confiscate the
land and other means of production owned by those who opposed the
reform and participated in the armed rebellion aimed at separating
Tibet from China, but redeemed the property of those who were not
involved in the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
The land, livestock and means of production so confiscated and
redeemed were distributed to the serfs, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changed Life of Former Tibetan Serf Owner (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As Soinam supported the reform and re-distributed his land and
houses to serfs and slaves, the newly-established people's
government let him serve as vice-chairman of the Shannan
Prefectural Committee of the CPPCC and he was satisfied with it.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Officials of various levels pay great attention to
members of the CPPCC and would ask us for advice before making an
important decision and give us feedback."
</P>
<P>
Soinam makes regular tours around Shannan to learn about people'
s living conditions, actions which are spoken highly of by local
people.
</P>
<P>
He has only one son, who is 50 years old and serves as general
manager of a local factory. His grandson and grand-daughter are
studying in middle schools in Tianjin Municipality and Changchun
city, capital of northeast China's Jilin Province, whose living
expenses and tuition fees are covered by the state.
</P>
<P>
Soinam gets a monthly salary of 2,027 yuan. Together with the
over 2,000 yuan monthly pay of his son and daughter-in-law, the
four-member family live a good life.
</P>
<P>
Soinam told reporters in his Tibet-styled house built of
granite and cement that he has finished writing his family's
history and will have the book published. He expressed the hope
that it will be translated into Chinese and other languages so
that more people will be able to learn about the past and present
of Tibet in an authentic and realistic way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
