<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Pandas Given As Gift To Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Two giant pandas have been
presented to Hong Kong from the Chinese central government as gift
in a bid to publicize the problems facing this endangered species.
</P>
<P>
The pair, An'an and Jiajia, are scheduled to leave for the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) on Thursday from
southwest China's Chengdu City.
</P>
<P>
For their first month in the HKSAR they will be in quarantine
before being housed in a specially built, state of the art
enclosure in Hong Kong's Ocean Theme park.
</P>
<P>
The female, Jiajia, is aged about 21, and is known in China as
a "heroin mother" after giving birth to six cubs in five
consecutive years from 1992 to 1996. She has been living with the
male An'an, aged about 14, in the Wolong Giant Panda Research
Center in Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese veterinary experts the pair are in good
health.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the HKSAR, the Central Government decided to
send the two giant pandas to Hong Kong as local people have been
expressing the wish that they might have their own pandas in
captivity and the authorities believe it will also increase public
awareness in the region for the need to protect nature and
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Giant pandas are considered to be one of world's most
endangered species and only about 1,000 are known to exist, most
of them in Sichuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
