<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Secretary Leaves UAE for Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen left the United Arab Emirates (UAE) for Qatar on Tuesday
morning, a source from the U.S. Embassy here told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Cohen left from Dubai for Qatar Tuesday morning, the source
said, adding that Qatar and Kuwait will be the last two legs of
his Mideast tour aimed at explaining U.S. policy on Iraq and
rallying support.
</P>
<P>
He had visited Oman, Saudi Arabia and Bahrain before coming to
the UAE.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan and
Cohen discussed the latest developments in the region,
particularly the situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Cohen told reporters later that Washington was not seeking the
break-up of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, we have said time and time again that Iraq's
integrity must be maintained. Our goal is one day to help bring
about a change in regime so that the people of Iraq can in fact
rejoin the international community as a full-fledged member,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
But during their talks, the two leaders did not mention the
U.S.-British air strikes against Iraq in mid-December, a UAE
official said.
</P>
<P>
"The position of the UAE has not changed. It is opposed to the
military strikes on Iraq and it favors a diplomatic solution
through the U.N. Security Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said the UAE is also "against any change of Iraqi
regime that is imposed from outside" and it supports Iraq's unity
and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has vowed to help the Iraqi opposition parties topple
the current regime led by President Saddam Hussein since it
launched four-night air strikes in December with a declared aim of
punishing Baghdad for not to cooperate with the U.N. weapons
inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
