<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prolonged Drought Causes Forest Fires in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The prolonged drought in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province caused four forest fires in three
counties between March 1 and 8, affecting 50 ha. of land.
</P>
<P>
The fires in Huaxian, Fuping and Zhouzhi counties were doused
by local people and soldiers, according to Dou Minsheng, an
official in charge of the provincial forest fire-control
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
But strong winds and dry weather made efforts to control the
fires very difficult, Dou said.
</P>
<P>
The provincial fire-control department has been on high alert
in case major fires break out.
</P>
<P>
According to meteorologists, rainfall in Shaanxi since last
October was 40 percent to 60 percent less than the normal.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the provincial forest fire-control department
said a total of 76 fires have occurred since last November. There
were 54 forest fires in February alone, which affected 890 ha. of
forestry land. However, the fires caused no heavy economic losses,
deaths or injuries.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Gaoshi, the director of the provincial forestry
department, said that measures have been adopted to prevent major
forest fires from starting, including strict regulations
concerning the lighting of fires in such areas.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi, which boasts many wild animals and rare plants, is
also home to giant pandas, golden monkeys and other endangered
animals.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province banned lumber activities and closed
many enterprises in order to protect the environment for wild
animals. Forest fires pose a serious threat to these precious
wild animals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
