<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Cases Rise Sharply in Israel in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Tuberculosis (TB) cases in
Israel rose by 47 percent in 1998 from 1997, but experts said it
is too early to draw final conclusions, the Haaretz daily reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It cited the latest data released by the Health Ministry as
saying that the TB cases increased from 422 in 1997 to 619 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Shem-Tov, head of the national unit in the Health
Ministry for TB and AIDS said the data is being analyzed and will
be discussed at a conference, which is scheduled for March 24 to
mark the World Tuberculosis Day.
</P>
<P>
Tunde Madaras, who takes charge of supervising TB for the
European branch of the World Health Organization (WHO), said that
one of the main reasons for the rise is the immigration from the
former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Last year, tuberculosis reached near-epidemic proportions in
the countries of the former Soviet Union, Madaras said.
</P>
<P>
TB is a bacterial disease caused by the Tuberculosis
mycobacterium and transmitted through the air. The bacteria can
lie dormant within an individual for several years, becoming
active when the immune system is weakened.
</P>
<P>
Signs of active pulmonary TB include fever, coughing, bloody
mucus and chest pains. Individuals can carry the disease and
infect others without experiencing any symptoms themselves.
</P>
<P>
The WHO recommends combating the disease by monitoring the
treatment to every person with TB. Shem-Tov instituted this method
in Israel in 1996.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the very serious problem of non-compliance, each
patient is assigned to one of the nine TB care centers around the
country, where health care workers watch them to make sure that
the medication dispensed is swallowed, Haaretz said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
