<HEADLINE> Vietnam Calls for Overcoming Toxic Chemicals' Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 9 (Xinhua)-- Vietnam's prime minister has called
for efforts to overcome the consequences of toxic chemicals used
during the Vietnam War, Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Phan Van Khai instructed the National Steering
Board for Overcoming Toxic Chemicals' Consequences to direct its
activities toward better efficiency in this aspect, according to
VNA.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese Foreign Ministry said in a recent announcement
that more than 2 million people in the country are affected by
toxic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister on March 3 also asked the board to cooperate
with the Ministry of Public Security and the Vietnam Red Cross in
studying how to achieve better international cooperation and
higher efficiency in this work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
