<HEADLINE> Vietnam's PM Orders Administrative Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Cabinet members and government
agency
heads in Vietnam have been asked to strictly adhere to the
government's work regulations and any absence from meetings is
only
acceptable if they are on overseas missions.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Phan Van Khai has issued an order that this year

ministers and heads of ministerial-level agencies are allowed to
go
abroad on mission only once at the most, except in special cases,
the
Saigon Times Daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Instead, they must spend time on tackling new problems,
mobilizing
all available sources for development and reinforcing
administration.
</P>
<P>
In order to realize this year's social and economic targets,
state
management should be strengthened and enterprises be inspected and

supervised to see if government measures and directions are
implemented, the prime minister said in the order.
</P>
<P>
Ministries and ministerial bodies must formulate detailed plans
on
personnel restructuring, administrative reform and measures
against
corruption, harassment and authoritarian attitudes, Khai said,
adding
that agencies must report monthly the implementation of their
plans.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister has also called for greater thrift and a
curtailment of unnecessary expenses. Giving gifts bought with
government money is strictly banned and ministers and ministerial
agencies chiefs should set a good example, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
