<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Non-Performing Loans Expected to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanahaeminda said Tuesday that non-performing loans (NPL) of
the country's corporate sector would fall from the current 45.9
percent to 30 percent of total lending by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said the declining trend of the NPLs was due to the
government's corporate debt restructuring program which had
started to bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
"The reform will even be speeded up after 11 key economic
reform bills are passed by the parliament without changes in their
major objectives," Tarrin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
If NPLs decreased, t would boost demand for loans, and
commercial banks, on the other hand, would be more willing to
extend loans to local firms, which would help spur the domestic
economy and strengthen the financial sector, Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
He said loans totaling 716.6 billion baht (19.4 billion U.S.
dollars) were in the process of restructuring talks, up from 690.5
billion baht (18.6 billion dollars) at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Bank for International Settlements (BIS) in Swizerland,
which acts as the central bank of other countries, also reported
that outstanding loans of Asian countries from international banks
had declined.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister
Supachai Panitchpakdi said Tuesday that the government was
considering revising the Banking Restructuring Program, another
crucial economic reform program in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"We have to take a serious look to see how measures included in
the program can be improved," he said, adding, "The measures are
sufficient in general, but there may be some problems to do with
the implementation."
</P>
<P>
He did not give other details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
