<HEADLINE> CPPCC Member Urges Increased Contact Between Hong Kong and Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hu Fa-kuang, chairman of the Ryoden Electric Engineering
Holdings Ltd. who also chairs the Liberal Democratic Federation of
Hong Kong, said at a CPPCC National Committee full-member meeting
this afternoon that increasing cooperation between Hong Kong and
the interior areas is crucial to Hong Kong's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
"But extended cooperation should be based on more frequent
contacts between officials of interior areas and their Hong Kong
counterparts, especially at higher levels so as to enhance mutual
understanding," Hu said, adding that more mainland officials
should visit Hong Kong to enhance their understanding of the place
and explore cooperative opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the central government allow Hong Kong business
people to invest in such sectors as telecommunications, power
generation, agriculture, retail sale and service trade. Meanwhile,
the interior areas can make use of Hong Kong's expertise in
marketing and sales promotion to help their export business.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's efforts to develop hi-tech industries need lots of
talented people. Hu suggested an exchange system be put in place
to swap university students or graduate students between Hong Kong
and the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province and the Hong Kong SAR government should
establish a liaison for coordinating efforts and achieving highest
possible economic returns in joint venture projects in land
utilization, environmental protection, waste water discharge and
transport network, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hu expressed concern over the housing reform in interior areas,
pointing out that difficulties the reform has encountered and
sluggish sales of commercial housing in the mainland result
largely from inadequate laws and regulations governing the
property market, in addition to weak residents' buying power.
</P>
<P>
He said mainland officials in charge of housing reform and real
estate developers should learn from Hong Kong's experience to
improve relevant policies in the mainland. 
</P>
