<HEADLINE> Lebanese Women Demand Service in Army, Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese women have called on the
government to give them opportunities to play a role in army and
cabinet, the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I entrust you with a message to President Emile
Lahoud: Lebanese women are asking to be included among the
conscripts for military service," said Judge Alice Aam at a
ceremony marking the International Women's Day, during which
Health Minister Karam Karam was present on behalf of the president.
</P>
<P>
Men will ultimately gain from such a move because it will
"minimize the duration of their military service," she added.
</P>
<P>
She called for an across-board abolition of discrimination
against women in laws relating to Lebanon's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Hayan Haidar, head of the local Family Planning Organization,
said he was disappointed at the lack of female representation in
the cabinet, contrary to expectations when Lahoud came to power
last November.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that women can make up for their lack of
representation in government by increasing their presence in other
bodies, such as the Social Economic Council which is soon to be
formed.
</P>
<P>
In Lebanese previous cabinets, there was no single woman
minister. In the 128-seat Parliament, there are currently only
three female deputies. 
</P>
