<HEADLINE> Western Envoy Reiterates Decision to Sack Serb President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 9 (Xinhua) -- High ranking representative of
the Peace Implementation Council (of Bosnia) Carlos Westendorp
said on Monday evening that he could not accept Serb Parliament's
rejection to his decision to sack Nikola Poplasen as president of
the Serb Republic.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Westendorp, a Spanish diplomat, reaffirmed that Poplasen
should no longer officiate as president of the Serb Republic, the
Yugoslav Tanjug news agency quoted Serb radio and TV as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to Serb representatives to accept the decision
of Roberts Owen, head of the arbitration tribunal and American
arbitrator, on setting up a neutral district in the Bosnian town
of Brcko and put it under international supervision.
</P>
<P>
The parliament passed a resolution on Sunday to reject the
decisions of Carlos Westendorp and Roberts Owen, both announced on
March 5, saying they violated related articles in the Dayton Peace
Accord.
</P>
<P>
Under the rule of the U.S.-brokered Dayton peace agreement that
ended the 1992-95 war, Brcko, a city with 90,000 population, is a
Serb entity. But the Muslim-Croat federation claimed its control
over the city which serves as a key port on the Sava river.
</P>
