<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (9) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From then on, the 13th Dalai Lama gradually learned the truth
and began to strengthen contacts with the central government.
</P>
<P>
In 1933, the 13th Dalai Lama passed away and the central
government sent Huang Musong to Tibet to confer titles of nobility,
hold memorial ceremonies for the 13th Dalai Lama and help
establish the Tibet office of the central government in Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
After that, Wu Zhongxin, head of the Mongolia-Tibet Commission
went all the way to Tibet for presiding over the celebrations for
the appointment of the 14th Dalai Lama. The move further promoted
relations between the central government and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Raiqen, living Buddha and regent, was elected as a
member of the central executive commission of the Kuomintang's
central committee.
</P>
<P>
All these triggered hatred from Britain and the pro-British
forces who managed to take over power from Raiqen by plots and
then they persecuted Raiqen to death later.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, fearing that the Chinese government would take
measures to reinforce sovereign administration over Tibet after
the second World War, the British authorities in April 1943 tried
to implement the policy of "giving up the recognition of China's
suzerainty over Tibet" and creating the independence of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
This was similar to 1912 when the British and Indian
governments termed Tibet as a protectorate of Britain in the name
of "abolishing China's suzerainty" according to the Memorandum
Respecting the Situation in the Countries Bordering on the North-
Eastern Frontier of India.
</P>
</TEXT>
