<HEADLINE> Japan Urged to Help Region Out of Economic Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Japan, with its regional and
global economic presence and strong profile, has a measure of
responsibility in assisting the region out of its current economic
 turmoil, a Malaysian official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz said the
public-private sector partnership approach that Japan has taken to
reach out to the regional economies can have a positive impact on
the region's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 21st annual meeting of Malaysia-Japan Economic
Associations here, Rafidah said Japanese investors should make
their own objective evaluation of Malaysia through a first-hand
feel of what the country is all about.
</P>
<P>
She said Japanese investors' confidence in Malaysia needs not
be determined by subjective analysis done by others on the
country's situation.
</P>
<P>
"The experiences of Japanese companies already operating in
Malaysia can serve as valuable reference," she said, adding that
the Japanese experience in Malaysia has undoubtedly been a good
one with its track record showing success.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, a total of 128 projects with Japanese equity in the
manufacturing sector were approved with capital investments of 1.9
billion ringgit (500 million U.S. dollars), of which 600 million
ringgit (157.89 million dollars) was pumped into 31 new projects
and 1.3 billion ringgit (342.11 million dollars) into expansion
and diversification.
</P>
<P>
Japanese investments in these projects accounted for 14.5
percent of total foreign investments in the manufacturing sector
in 1998 which stood at 13.1 billion ringgit (3.45 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to Rafidah, 20 Japanese companies are currently
establishing their international procurement centers in Malaysia,
36 have set up representative offices, six have regional offices
and five have their operational headquarters here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
