<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The British Foreign Office, in a report called "Issues of Tibet
and China's Suzerainty", believed that maintaining its recognition
of China's suzerainty over Tibet might "hinder our freedom of
directly signing agreements with Tibet".
</P>
<P>
The British authorities, after consultation between their
Foreign Office and the Indian Office, did not dare to allow even
the "independence" of Tibet in name, fearing that the act would
give rise to the central government sending troops to Tibet. In
this case, the Tibetans could not resist while the British
authorities could not directly support the "independence of Tibet".
</P>
<P>
Despite the facts, British foreign secretary Anthony Eden
insisted in letter on calling Tibet a complete autononous region
in fact and opposing China's "attempt to retake control of Tibet".
The British authorities tried to persuade the Chinese government
to hold a conference similar to the Simla Conference and agree to
their "legal" division of Tibet through agreements. The Chinese
government did not consider at all the absurd requests and the
British authorities' attempts failed.
</P>
<P>
After that, Britain and the pro-British forces of Tibet's upper
class launched various splittist activities but failed to achieve
their premeditated targets.
</P>
<P>
In a word, in the past 100 years, the British authorities have
tried in various ways to invade Tibet, especially fostered pro-
British forces of the upper class in Tibet, in an effort to split
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
