<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (11) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
II. "Independence of Tibet" is a pawn on the chessboard of the
imperialist cold war policy.
</P>
<P>
Since the ending of the Second World War, great changes have
taken place in the political structure of the world, with the U.S.
rising to be the strongest capitalist country. During the period
between the end of the war and the middle of the 1970s, the U.S.
government, in its pursuit of a "cold war" policy, inherited the
mantle of the British Empire and spared no efforts in supporting
the Tibetan separatists in their activities aimed at the
independence of Tibet, in attempting to subvert, dismember and
weaken the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
As early as the end of 1942 when the Chinese people were
fighting a bloody war against the Japanese aggressors, U.S
intelligence departments had considered Tibet as a strategic
measure. Capt. Ilia Tolstoy and Lieut. Brooke Dolan were sent to
Tibet carrying gifts from President Roosevelt to the Dalai Lama,
ostensibly to investigate the possibility of building a highway to
transfer materials for the war against Japanese aggression.
</P>
<P>
Tolstoy also incited the local Tibetan authorities to think
about participating in the post-war peace conference, claiming
that the U.S. government fully sympathized with the small and weak
countries that hope to maintain their independence. The Chinese
Foreign Ministry lodged a protest with the U.S.State Department
following the two men's promise that the U.S. government would
support Tibet's independence from China.
</P>
<P>
Soon afterwards, the intelligence departments presented three
radio transmitters to the local Tibetan government to rope in the
latter in the scheme, and from that point the U.S. government
began to encourage Tibet to seek independence in the hope of
turning it into an anti-Communist base in the future.
</P>
<P>
After the Second World War, the Soviet and East European
socialist block were in direct confrontation with the U.S.-led
capitalist block. Against this political backdrop, China's civil
war was drawing to an end and the Communist Party of China (CPC)
was on the verge of liberating the whole country.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the U.S. State Department began to
discuss policies that the U.S. government could adopt in regards
to Tibet. Some argued that Tibet is of great significance
ideologically and strategically and if the CPC won the civil war,
the U.S. should not continue to regard Tibet as China's territory.
They proposed to send U.S. officials to Lhasa immediately to
establish secret relations in advance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (12) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The State Department concluded that in light of the friendly
relations between the U.S. and the Chiang Kai-shek administration,
the U.S. would not publicize its attitude for changing China's
sovereignty over Tibet at that particular time, but it added that
in case China fell into Communist hands, it would be more
beneficial to the U.S. to recognize Tibet's independence than to
regard it as part of China ruled by the CPC. One way of supporting
Tibet's independence was to formally raise the issue at the U.N.
General Assembly, it suggested.
</P>
<P>
In 1949, the landslide victory of the people's revolution led by
the CPC threw Tibet's high-level separatists into chaos. On the
one hand, they expelled officials of the Kuomintang government
from Tibet and prepared for war; and on the other, they sought
help from the U.S. and U.K. by sending telegraphs and a delegation,
which was stopped in India.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government also eagerly looked forward to giving a
helping hand to Tibet. When Lowell Thomas, a U.S. reporter and
writer, and his son got to Tibet, they appealed to the U.S.to
provide anti-Communist support and to send a delegation to Lhasa,
which had a great propaganda effect.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government's plan to send a delegation to Tibet and
provide material aid was dropped for fear of being blocked by the
Indian government.
</P>
<P>
In June 1950, when the Korean War broke out, the U.S. was
determined to turn Tibet into a link of its chain for an oriental
strategic encirclement under the banner of worldwide anti-
Communist activists.
</P>
<P>
On June 13, the U.S. State Department sent a statement to
Britain's ambassador to the U.S., saying that it would probably
take action to encourage and support Tibet's ambitions to cast off
China's rule.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) advanced rapidly
toward Tibet and liberated Qamdo, which forced the local Tibetan
authorities to send a delegation to Beijing headed by Ngapoi
Ngawang Jime to negotiate peace.
</P>
<P>
On May 23, 1951, the historical 17-article agreement for the
peaceful liberation of Tibet was signed, which completely foiled
the scheme by U.S. and Tibetan separatists to obstruct the PLA's
plans for liberating Tibet.
</P>
</TEXT>
