<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (13) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After the peaceful liberation of Tibet, some Western countries
headed by the United States of America continued to provide
powerful support and aid to the Tibetan separatists. A political
instructor told Tibetan trainees at a camp in Colorado that China
was very powerful and was imposing threats on the free world;
however China was not yet rich but if one day it became rich, the
threat would grow bigger. He said the strategy was to cut it apart
when it's still impoverished. First the aim was to cut away Tibet,
then Xinjiang, then Inner Mongolia and lastly, Manchuria, leaving
a plot of land for the Han Chinese. Only thus was it possible to
make China weak and unable to threaten the free world, he said. He
told the Tibetan trainees that they must shoulder the important
task of splitting Tibet from China and that was the reason that
they were there to receive training."
</P>
<P>
Since 1951, The U.S. has supported the "Independence of Tibet"
activities of the Tibetan separatists in the following areas:
</P>
<P>
1. The CIA continued to have contacts and negotiations with the
Tibetan separatist force on ways and forms of support. The Dalai
Lama's brothers Gyalo Toinzhub and Tubdain Thubten maintained
particularly close contacts with CIA. The U.S. has on many
occasions encouraged the Dalai Lama to overthrow the 17-article
agreement signed between the local Tibetan government and the
Central People's Government on peaceful liberation of Tibet,
directed him to submit petitions for American aid to "confront the
Chinese Communist Government, to facilitate the American
government's "legal" and open support of the Tibetan separatists.
In addition, they also planned and arranged the Dalai Lama's
flight from China.
</P>
<P>
2. Since 1956, the CIA trained many Tibetan separatists in its
training camps in Saipan, Colorado and some other places. The camp
in Colorado alone trained 170 spies. They were sent back to the
Tibetan habitats in Sichuan, Qinghai, Yunan provinces and Tibet to
engage in rebellion and other destructive activities.
</P>
<P>
The Eisenhower Administration first gave approval in September
1958 to supply arms, ammunition, grain and other supplies to the
Tibetan separatists. Since the end of 1958, the CIA air-dropped a
great amount of equipment including guns, heavy machine guns and
mortars at the Tibetan separatists' camps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
