<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (14) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
3. The CIA made a meticulous plan and provided guns for the
massive armed rebellion by the Tibetan aristocrats on March 10,
1959. Spies trained by CIA accompanied the Dalai Lama in his
flight to India. On May 20, 1959, the confidential "303 Commission
" of the US government approved the first batch of aid to the
Dalai Lama, who had just arrived in India.
</P>
<P>
4. Following the rebellion failed in March 1959, the U.S. led
some other countries at a United Nations congress in submitting a
draft on the so-called "Tibet Issue", attacking China's crushing
of the rebellion. They managed to list the "Tibet Issue" on the UN'
s agenda three times in 1960, 1961 and 1965 and had their anti-
China drafts approved in 1961 and 1965.
</P>
<P>
5. After the rebellion failed in March 1959, the CIA gathered 2,
100 rebels and stationed them at a place in Nepal adjacent to
Tibet. The number of rebels at that base later increased to 15,000.
They survived on funding covered by the US government which
included the supply of arms and equipment. They frequently sneaked
into Tibet and engaged in destructive activities for as along as
eight years.
</P>
<P>
6. According to the latest decoded American confidential
documents, for most of the 1960s, the CIA provided the Dalai Group
1.7 million U.S. dollars every year to help it carry out anti-
China activities. The funding includes 180,000 US dollars in
annual personal subsidies for the Dalai Lama. After 1968, the CIA
reduced the funding to 1.2 million US dollars and closed the
training camp in Colorado.
</P>
