<HEADLINE> EU Provides $90M for Projects in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will spend
approximately 75 million euros (about 90 million U.S. dollars)
this year in implementing various projects in Zambia, Times of
Zambia newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The projects are part of a vast on-going eighth European
Development Fund (EDF) five-year program which has a potential
total capital outlay of 257 million euros (about 308 million
dollars), EU counsellor Guy Rijcken told the newspaper during an
interview,
</P>
<P>
Of the 22 projects which the EU is expected to undertake during
the five- year time frame, 11 have been approved and money has
already been committed, three are near approval, five are making
good progress in the approval process while three others are under
consideration, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The approved programs include the private sector development
program which is aimed at supporting enterprise development and
intermediary organization capacity building as well as foreign
investment promotion.
</P>
<P>
There is also the Zambia education capacity building program
which is aimed at improving access to education and training to
vulnerable groups.
</P>
<P>
The others include tourism and wildlife development program
which involves preparation of a medium term tourism strategy and
action plan for Zambia, said the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
