<HEADLINE> Govt of National Unity in Zimbabwe Ruled Out: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean ruling party's secretary
for legal affairs Eddison Zvobgo has ruled out the possibility of
the formation of a government of national unity as demanded by
opposition political parties, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Zvobgo told journalists attending a media and the constitution
workshop Monday in Bulawayo, the country's second largest city,
that opposition parties under the National Convention for Change
(NCC) were advocating for transitional government which would be
responsible for drafting a people's oriented constitution.
</P>
<P>
"These opposition parties are trying to get in government
through the backdoor without winning elections," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The suggestion to form a national unity government is rejected
outright and there is no negotiation on that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zvobgo, who is also Minister Without Portfolio, said a national
unity government was only possible when people had gone to war and
there was no outright winner.
</P>
<P>
He said some of the opposition parties had never participated
in elections, yet they wanted to use the drafting of a new
constitution as a method of getting into power.
</P>
<P>
"No one from any opposition party will get into government
without winning elections," said Zvobgo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
