<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (16) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since the 1980s, the international anti-China forces have been
using the support of the Dalai group's "independence of Tibet" and
"high degree of self-autonomy" as a pretext to stage the following
activities against China:
</P>
<P>
1. After several large-scale riots in Lhasa, instigated by the
Dalai Lama group, and the "Beijing Incident", the West conferred
the Nobel Peace Prize on the Dalai Lama in 1989, aiming to reward
and encourage him for his decades-long efforts to split China as
well as to raise his political status. With the title of a Nobel
Peace Prize laureate", the Dalai Lama was able to carry out his
activities and deceive the international community more easily.
</P>
<P>
2. Some western countries invited the Dalai Lama for visits one
after another. And some high-ranking government officials received
him and other heads of his "government-in-exile" formally and
informally. Since 1989, the Dalai Lama has visited, by invitation,
more than 50 countries and regions in Europe, the Americas, Asia
and Australia, some of which he has been to many times, and or
once a year. Heads of state, prime ministers and other important
government officials from scores of nations have met or held talks
with the Dalai Lama, some of whom even went so far as to make
statements, declarations or appeals either to pep up the Dalai
Lama or put pressure on the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
3. Anti-China forces across the world have been seeking the
support of parliaments to prop up the Dalai group. Western
countries, however, have established diplomatic relations with
China, so their governments would not deny China's sovereignty
over Tibet and yet overtly support Tibet's independence. They
choose to take low profiles while letting their parliaments take
the lead.
</P>
<P>
With the Dalai group staging worldwide propaganda, the U.S.
House of Representatives was the first to adopt a bill in June
1987 on the "Tibet issue" to support the Dalai group. Later in
September, the House invited the Dalai Lama to visit the United
States, where he made speeches and put forward the so-called "five-
point peaceful proposals". And soon after, some anti-China
Congressmen raised the "amendment to human rights issues in Tibet".
In 1991, the House passed a motion recognizing that the Dalai Lama
and his "government-in-exile" were the "genuine representative" of
the Tibetan people and claiming that Tibet was an "occupied
country". In September 1993, the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee also made a proposal calling for the setting up of an
office of the United States Information Agency in Tibet, in an
attempt to establish relations of a diplomatic nature with the
Dalai "government-in-exile". In recent years, parliaments of
various countries have drawn up dozens of bills or resolutions on
the so-called "Tibet issue".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (17) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
4. The United Nations has been used as an arena for the anti-
China activities focused on the "Tibet issue". In August 1989, the
West raised a motion to review the "human rights issues in Tibet"
at the U.N. group session on preventing discrimination and
protecting minority ethnic groups. And at the 46th session of the
U.N. Human Rights Commission in 1990, Western countries cooked up
some draft resolutions including "human rights in Tibet", in a
move to have them listed on the session's agenda. In 1991, some
Western countries again raised the "Tibet issue" and had the anti-
China resolution on the Tibet situation passed at the group
session, "appealing" to the Chinese government to fully respect
the "basic human rights and freedom of the Tibetan people". In
1992, the countries once again put forward a proposal on the "
Chinese Tibet situation" at the session of the U.N. Human Rights
Commission. On similar occasions in the following years, some
countries repeatedly raised the motion on so-called "human rights
in Tibet", but they failed to have them passed due to opposition
from most member states.
</P>
<P>
5. Anti-China forces in the world have been making use of the
semi-official, non-governmental organizations to summon support in
the name of "mass organizations". They have written letters to the
sessions of the U.N. Human Rights Commission", organized
receptions, public lectures, demonstrations, and sits-in, given
out leaflets and lobbied government officials or pushed them to
show concern about and support to the "Tibet issue". They also
made speeches at many international organizations, distorting and
attacking China's policies on Tibet. In addition, they financed to
the tune of millions of U.S. dollars a number of movies including
"Kundun" and "Seven Years in Tibet" to enhance the Dalai Lama and
the Nazis and vilify China. They showed the anti-China films in
Europe and America to deceive the world. They even sponsored some
"benefit performances in support of Tibet" and "Tibet freedom
concerts" by inviting a number of stars to perform in such cities
as Paris, to extensively whip up public opinion.
</P>
</TEXT>
