<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Party Forms Political Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Israel's biggest opposition
Labor Party signed an agreement with the Meimad party in Tel Aviv
Monday night to join forces in contesting the May 17 elections,
local media reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By doing so, the Labor has fulfilled its task of forming a
political alliance with Gesher led by former foreign minister
David Levy and the moderate religious movement Meimad before the
elections.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, which had already been approved by Labor
Central Committee last week, Meimad will be given one cabinet post
and three slots in the top 40 of the Knesset (parliament) under
an umbrella list called One Israel led by Labor leader Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
After signing the agreement, Barak praised his new Meimad
partners for giving his One Israel the Jewish, religious and
democratic support it needs to survive.
</P>
<P>
By merging with Meimad, Labor and Gesher have built a
broad-based, populist and democratic community that will properly
serve the occasion, Barak said.
</P>
<P>
Gesher approved the union with Labor and Meimad on Sunday
and signed the unity agreement with Labor the same day.
</P>
<P>
Levy got the No. 3 slot on the alliance's list for the next
Knesset just behind Barak and former prime minister Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Third Way party, one of the coalition partners
of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Likud Party, unanimously
approved Monday night Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani to
continue to serve as party leader.
</P>
<P>
The decision was seen as a foregone conclusion as Kahalani was
the only candidate for the post and the party is expected to
choose its Knesset list next week.
</P>
<P>
Talks among Israel's right-wing parties aimed at forging a
united nationalist bloc to contest in the May elections were also
under way.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Herut, Tekuma and Moledet parties met Monday
night in Tel Aviv again to try to close a deal.
</P>
<P>
Their joint platform, mostly focused on objecting to the peace
process with Palestinians, is nearly finished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
