<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Expressways To Exceed 10,000 KM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- China will lift its total mileage
of expressways to more than 10,000 kilometers before the end of
next year, according to a senior transportation official who is
here attending the ongoing annual session of the National People's
Congress, China's legislature.
</P>
<P>
Vice Minister of Communications Li Juchang said construction
of expressways linking Beijing and Shanghai, Beijing and Shenyang
in the northeast and several others in eastern and southwestern
China is in full swing. Sections of the expressways are expected
to be completed and opened to traffic by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
During the 1999-2000 period, he said, China will build an
additional 3,750 km of expressways.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 285 major highways are under construction, with a
combined length of more than 27,000 kilometers, of which 12,600 km
are expressways, Li said, adding that total cost for these highway
and expressway projects will amount to more than 500 billion yuan
(about 62.5 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The proactive financial policy that has been implemented since
early last year to stimulate domestic demand has served as a shot
to the arm for road construction. Last year alone, investment in
the sector reached 218.8 billion yuan, a sharp rise over the
budgeted figure of 120 billion yuan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hefty funding last year added about 37,000 kilometers to the
country's total highway mileage and helped eased transportation
bottlenecks, Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
