<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Myanmar to Crack Down on Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Thailand have agreed
to jointly crack down on narcotics trafficking and production
wherever the location, Thai government spokesman Akapol
Sorasuchart said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Akapol said Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai and his visiting
Myanmar counterpart, Gen. Than Shwe, announced a long-term joint
drug suppression plan during talks in Chiang Rai, northern
Thailand, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the two neighboring countries would set up a
joint committee, which would comprise senior officials from
anti-narcotic agencies of both sides to hold regular talks aimed
at exchanging views and laying out concrete programs on joint drug
suppression.
</P>
<P>
Chuan also raised a proposal that Bangkok and Rangoon cooperate
in the short term as well to end narcotic production along the
border, especially amphetamine factories, Akapol disclosed.
</P>
<P>
He quoted Than Shwe as saying Myanmar would imitate Thailand's
projects initiated by King Bhumibol Adulyadej to replace opium
cultivation with cash crops.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand, as requested by the Myanmar leader, agreed to
help Myanmar by sending narcotic experts to Rangoon soon to
transfer knowledge on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Turning to disputes over border and territorial waters, Akapol
said the two sides agreed to discuss a joint patrol in the Andaman
Sea at the upcoming meeting of the Regional Border Committee of
the two countries and to hold talks more regularly to exchange
information and lay out plans aimed at effectively solving the
problems.
</P>
<P>
The disputes led to recent clashes between the naval forces of
the two countries resulting in deaths on both sides.
</P>
<P>
Akapol said Chuan also accepted Gen. Than Shwe's invitation to
visit Rangoon, but no date had been set. The Myanmar leader was
granted an audience by King Bhumibol Adulyadej on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gen. Than Shwe will return home Tuesday, ending a two-day
official visit to Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
