<HEADLINE> Growth In China's Ceramics Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The ceramics industry in China has
been enjoying fast growth and has become the world's largest, with
more than 9.9 billion items produced annually.
</P>
<P>
The country has been developing new technology and equipment to
improve production, according to Liu Jingzhou, deputy-head of the
China Council for the Promotion of International Trade's Building
Materials Branch.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 1,000 ceramics companies with exports to
150 countries and regions, worth 1.09 billion US dollars. Key
ceramics production bases are at Tangshan and Handan in Hebei
province, Zibo in Shandong, Yixing in Jiangsu, and Jingdezhen in
Jiangxi.
</P>
<P>
It has research and design institutes and a large group of
specialized ceramics producers using advanced technology and
equipment to reduce pollution and cut energy consumption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To compete with the Tsarist Russia, Britain started to achieve
its goal of invading Tibet with armed forces in the 1880s. Using
the excuse of trading negotiations by Macaulay, a financial
secretary of Bengal province of the Indian government, Britain
launched the first large-scale war invading Tibet in 1888.
</P>
<P>
The corrupt Qing Dynasty government was compelled to sign two
treaties which resulted in national betrayal and humiliation which
enabled Britain to seize enormous benefits politically,
economically and in territorial terms.
</P>
<P>
Ambitious George N. Curzon, appointed to be the Indian governor
in the early 20th century, immediately carried out principles of
striving for supremacy in central Asia against Tsarist Russia, and
turning China's Tibet into a "buffer state" through the use of
force, and in reality a dependency of Britain.
</P>
<P>
Curzon, in a bid to change Tibet's political status in China's
territory and remove China's sovereignty over Tibet, distorted "
sovereignty" into "suzerainty." He further depreciated "suzerainty
" into a political fabrication and affectation.
</P>
<P>
Curzon even proposed that Britain directly make contact with
Tibet without reporting to the Chinese government in an attempt to
split Tibet from China.
</P>
<P>
Britain launched its second large-scale war of aggression in
Tibet in 1903-1904 after its plots were severely resisted and
forced the Tibetan local government to sign an illegal treaty
known as the "Lhasa Convention."
</P>
<P>
The British army's slaughter of Tibetans resulted in brave
resistance among the Tibetan army and people as well as bringing
stern condemnation from various provinces. The Tsarist Russia also
lodged a protest for the purpose of safeguarding its own
imperialist interests.
</P>
<P>
Taking into consideration preparations for a war against
Germany and trade with China, Britain again changed its plans for
invading Tibet by roping in elements from the upper echelons of
Tibetan society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese expert in Tibetan
studies has published a signed article to criticize overseas anti-
China forces and the Dalai Lama clique which advocate the "
independence of Tibet" in an attempt to split China.
</P>
<P>
The author, Feng Shiwen, points out that the so-called "Tibetan
independence" is in fact an outcome of foreign aggressions and has
been utilized by imperialists to split China over the past two
centuries.
</P>
<P>
It took three periods for imperialists and the international
anti-China forces to split China by advocating "Tibetan
independence", the author says. The article continues:
</P>
<P>
I. "Independence of Tibet" is an outcome of imperialistic
countries' attempt to turn Tibet into their dependency.
</P>
<P>
The issue of "Tibetan independence" was initially created by
Britain which had plotted to turn Tibet into one of its
dependencies since the late 18th century.
</P>
<P>
In order to separate Tibet from China, Britain had tried out
different ways, such as occupying the territory after establishing
trade relations, instigating the pro-Britain upper class elements
of Tibet, and launching wars of aggression.
</P>
<P>
The East India Company of Britain committed the first
aggression against China's Tibet in the late 18th century after it
annexed the territories of Bangladesh. Similar to its actions in
India, the company planned to establish trade relations with
locals at first, then stir up disputes and occupy the territory
with armed forces.
</P>
<P>
In 1774 and 1783, the company respectively sent its employees G.
Bogle and S. Turner to Xigaze with the aim of winning over the
Sixth Panchen Lama and other senior officials in an attempt to sow
dissension between Tibet and the central government of the Qing
Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
However, the Panchen Lama refused to be an ally of Britain. The
Qing government also prohibited British businessmen from going to
Lhasa and interior areas via Tibet, and later promulgated the
Authorized Regulations for the Better Government of Tibet in order
to tighten control over foreign affairs there.
</P>
<P>
Then, Britain launched a series of wars against Tibet's
neighbors Nepal, Sikkim and Bhutan in the half a century period
between 1814-1864, and forced them to be its dependencies, and
also the base for invading Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tsarist Russia intensified its activities of
aggression against Tibet by sending spies and so-called "
geographical exploration teams" into the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Independence of Tibet": Outcome of Foreign Aggression (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In late 1905 and early 1906, the British Indian government, its
executive official to Sikkim J.C. White, and business agent to
Gyaze Captain O'Connor plotted to lure the Ninth Panchen Lama to
India for a meeting with a British prince. The attempt was aimed
at controlling Tibet through the Panchen instead of Dalai.
</P>
<P>
O'Connor saw this plot as a means of consolidating his
friendship with the Panchen Lama, and even to subsidize and
protect him if necessary.
</P>
<P>
The Captain clearly pointed out that this action was to
counteract possible measures to be taken by Chinese government in
order to re-establish its authority in Tibet. That is to say, the
action was for resisting and rejecting China's sovereignty over
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
To make use of the extremely high prestige that the Panchen
Lama enjoyed among the Tibetans, O'Connor said that the Panchen's
activities in Tibet would arouse great excitement and adoration,
just like Christ appearing among Europeans.
</P>
<P>
He wrote to White that Britain had in its grasp the most
valuable card. It should make use of the opportunity to impress
the Panchen with Britain's generosity and power. Britain would
then win the Panchen's friendship and trust at a very small cost
so as to complete the "cause" of action that would otherwise cost
millions of pounds, involve battles, the signing of treaties and
stationing of armed troops in the region.
</P>
<P>
There is no other evidence that can so clearly explain that the
"cause" of the British government was to invade and split Tibet,
and why the British government would like to rope in the Panchen
Lama to achieve their aims.
</P>
<P>
A plan mapped out by the British-Indian government saw the
first step as opening a business agency and station an armed
escort in Xigaze in an attempt to prevent the Lhasa government or
the Chinese government, which had a grudge against the Panchen, to
take any measures. The business agency would be generally regarded
by the people as a security guard for the Panchen Lama.
</P>
<P>
It was very obvious that Britain tried first of all to bring
rear Tibet into its sphere of influence so as to reject China's
sovereignty there.
</P>
<P>
However, owing to a warning that the Chinese government made to
the British government, the Panchen Lama made his Indian trip and
refused to kneel in front of the British prince and thus refused
to yield to Britain.
</P>
<P>
Also due to the rapid development of Britain's preparation for
a war against Germany, the British government finally had to give
up its plot of splitting China's Tibet by drawing the Panchen Lama
onto its side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Police Bust Car Stealing Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 9 (Xinhua) --The police in Chengdu, capital of
southwest China's Sichuan Province, have bust up a large car-
stealing ring and arrested 36 suspects.
</P>
<P>
The ring, the biggest of its kind ever uncovered in the
province, stole 62 vehicles worth 18 million yuan over the past
couple of years, including Audi, Toyata and other name-brand
limousines. Now 14 vehicles have been recovered.
</P>
<P>
Xie Ergen, one of the suspects, was arrested on the Chengdu-
Jiuzhaigou road on September 25 as he was driving a cross-country
car claimed missing by the city's Binjiang Hotel on September 23.
</P>
<P>
This led to the discovery of the ring. About 27 other suspects
are still at large and further investigations are underway.
</P>
</TEXT>
