<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: California Has Highest Aggressive Driving Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 8 (Xinhua) -- A study released Monday by the
U.S. Surface Transportation Policy Project found that California
had the highest number of aggressive driving deaths in 1996, the
most recent available.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Riverside/San Bernardino, California-region
had an average of 13.4 deaths per 100,000 people, while Boston had
only 2.1 aggressive driving deaths per 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The Surface Transportation Policy Project, a group backed by
200 environmental groups, believes that a community like Boston, a
city with a reputation for bad drivers, has a lower rate because
it offers commuters options like the subway, commuter trains and
an extensive sidewalk network.
</P>
<P>
The Riverside/San Bernardino area, by contrast, is near Los
Angeles, a region with few mass transit options, overcrowded
freeways and a tradition of driving vast distances, the project
says.
</P>
<P>
"The endless strip malls and high-speed roads we are building
seem to be a breeding ground for aggressive driving," said Roy
Kientiz, executive director for the group that advocates mass
transit alternatives to traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
The Surface Transportation Policy Project's report was based on
its analysis of 1996. Like the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, the group defined aggressive driving as speeding
over 80 mph, tailgating, failing to yield and improper passing,
among other factors. It eliminated accidents in which drugs or
alcohol were a factor.
</P>
<P>
The aggressive driving report was criticized by The Road
Information Program, which noted a recent survey said aggressive
driving is triggered by congestion and slow-moving traffic --
evidence of the need to build more roads.
</P>
<P>
Since 1970, the group said, highway travel has increased by 130
percent while new road mileage has increased by only 5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
