<HEADLINE> Coffee Production Doubles in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's coffee yield has more than
doubled from 22,278 tons in the 1997-1998 period to 47,061 tons
in the 1998-1999 period which started last October, the figures
released by the Coffee Board of Kenya (CBK) said.
</P>
<P>
The board said Monday that the five commercial coffee mills in
Kenya have already received bookings of 4,338 tons of coffee still
in the fields.
</P>
<P>
The statistics given by the CBK shows that the mills are
holding 21,365 tons of unmilled coffee and another 21,358 tons of
milled coffee that is ready for auction.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the coffee will be milled by the Kenya Planters
Cooperative Union (KPCU), the Kenya's leading coffee miller.
According to the statistics, KPCU expects to mill 37,013 tons of
coffee, up from 19,496 tons in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The CBK said that the KPCU has received bookings for 3,166-ton
coffee in the fields and has 18,788 tons of unmilled coffee and
15,059 tons of clean coffee in its store.
</P>
<P>
However, Director Abraham Mwangi of the KPCU Board said that
coffee farming was still viable, provided farmers got the
necessary financial support.
</P>
<P>
Mwangi, who also heads a coffee research foundation, said that
his foundation has adequate coffee seedlings for farmers willing
to plant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
