<HEADLINE> 4,000 Congolese Refugees Enter Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Over 4,000 refugees have entered
Zambia in the past few days following renewed military activities
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Dominik Batsch, spokesman of the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) in Lusaka, said Monday
preliminary indications are that the refugees sought protection
from rebel advances southwest of DRC's Moba district on Lake
Tanganyika toward the direction of Pweto which resulted in
indiscriminate attacks against military and civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR representative Oluseyi Bajulaiye said a joint mission
comprising officials from UNHCR and the office of the Commissioner
for Refugees of the Ministry of Home Affairs is currently
assessing the situation in the area.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Zambian newspaper, the Post, quoted Bajulaiye as
saying: "Our main concern is to ensure the expeditious supply of
food and other relief items to the affected refugee population."
</P>
<P>
"In close collaboration with the provincial and district
authorities, transit facilities are presently being identified to
relocate the Congolese refugees," he said.
</P>
<P>
Batsch explained that the emergency response mechanism
contained in the contingency plan had been fully activated.
</P>
<P>
He said some 200 refugees were initially reported to have
entered Zambia last Thursday but the number grew rapidly to 2,000
new arrivals on Friday and topped 4,000 by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that another 500 refugees are reportedly close to
the border and may cross into Zambia any time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
