<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Starts Registration of Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Ghana has begun an exercise to
register foreigners to assist the security agencies to identity
foreigners when the need arises.
</P>
<P>
Kodjo Honari Okae, deputy director of Ghana Immigration Service
(GIS) in charge of operations, said the service would, after "a
reasonable period", begin to inspect identity cards (ID) which
are expected to give the foreigners confidence that they are
registered in the country, the Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
With the exception of tourists, landlords and hoteliers are
expected to demand ID cards before accepting foreigners into their
premises.
</P>
<P>
Okae said such an action on the part of landlords and hoteliers
would compel foreigners to register.
</P>
<P>
Under the exercise, which started Monday, all aliens would buy
a registration form for 10,000 cedis (about four U.S. dollars) and
pay an additional registration fee of 20,000 cedis (8.5 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Every foreigner would be required to submit four passport-size
pictures in person to the GIS which would issue them with a
registration card after processing their particulars.
</P>
<P>
He advised foreigners without passports to register since a
passport is not a condition for registration.
</P>
<P>
Okae said the exercise is not the same as issuing them with
resident permits, explaining that one needs a reason for permanent
stay such as schooling or working to obtain a resident permit.
</P>
<P>
"The registration covers even those on long visits and project
tours."
</P>
<P>
The official said the exercise would be a continuous one,
adding there will be regular checks by GIS personnel to ensure
that all aliens have registered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Abolish Fingerprinting of All Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government on Tuesday
endorsed a bill to revise the Alien Registration Law to abolish
fingerprinting for all foreign residents in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The revision, approved at a cabinet meeting, proposes to
require non-permanent foreign residents aged 16 and older living
more than one year in Japan to give a signature instead of a
fingerprint, and submit information on family members, when
registering at local municipal offices.
</P>
<P>
With the passage of the bill, Japan's fingerprinting system,
which has been criticized since it was introduced in 1952 as
treating foreigners like criminals, will be abolished.
</P>
<P>
Japan abolished compulsory fingerprinting for foreigners with
permanent resident status in a revision of the law in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese cabinet also approved a bill to revise the
Immigration Control and Refugees Recognition law to make illegally
staying in Japan a punishable offense separate from illegal entry.
</P>
<P>
Under the current law, offenders found to have illegally stayed
in Japan three years or more after illegally entering the country
can only be deported and not prosecuted for the crime of illegal
entry.
</P>
<P>
With the revision, illegally staying in Japan will become a "
continuing offense" and offenders could be sentenced to up to
three years in prison, or fined up to 300,000 yen (about 2,460 U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President Starts Ground-Breaking Visit to Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
left here on Tuesday morning for his ground-breaking visit to
Europe since he took office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's plane took off for Rome at 0800 local times (0430 GMT)
and he was seen off by Iranian First Vice President Hassan Habibi
and his office chief Mohammad Golpaygani.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, accompanied by Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi,
Minister of Mines and Metal Eshaq Jahangiri and some other senior
officials, will discuss with Italian leaders to strengthen
political, economic and cultural relations between the two
countries, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president will also meet Pope John Paul II at
Vatican City during his visit to Italy and then fly to France on
April 12.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kharrazi on Monday expressed hope that
Khatami's visit to Rome would help the westerners better
appreciate the factual realities in Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that the visit is in response to the good feelings of
Italian officials towards Iran and to their keenness on broadening
relations with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that Iran has always been keen to have close
relations with all nations in the world, including those in Europe,
on the basis of mutual respect and commitment to tension-easing.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and European countries warmed up after
Khatami initiated a foreign policy of detente and tension-easing
and opened a new chapter for Iran's foreign relations with the
world, particularly with the Gulf states and the European
countries.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Khatami's policy, Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
paid a visit to Iran in July, leading Italy as the pioneer in
Europe to improve relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Political observers believe that Khatami's visit to Italy and
the sequent visit to France will help him break the western
countries' policy to isolate Iran led by the U.S. since the
Islamic revolution in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
