<HEADLINE> Hornets Name Silas New Head Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Paul Silas took over as the
Charlotte Hornets' new coach Monday, pledging to try to revive a
franchise beset by poor play, weak leadership and injuries.
</P>
<P>
"Where this thing is going, who the heck knows? Hopefully
miracles do happen," Silas said after running a nearly two-hour
practice at the team's training complex.
</P>
<P>
Cowens, who led Charlotte to back-to-back 50 victory seasons in
his first two years in Charlotte, stepped down because of mounting
frustration with owner George Shinn's refusal to give him a raise.
</P>
<P>
Cowen's inability to work out a deal with Shinn was just one of
several problems associated with a club that is off to a 4-11
start and has seen a significant drop in attendance.
</P>
<P>
Shinn is the target of a lawsuit accusing him of unwanted
sexual advances, and some fans are calling on him to sell the team
if he confines to refuse to pay the money needed to retain top
talent.
</P>
<P>
Injuries have sidelined the team's best two players, and one of
them, leading scorer Glen Rice, is the subject of ongoing trade
talks with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
Silas coached the Clippers when they were located in San Diego
from 1980-83, compiling a 78-168 mark. He has been an NBA
assistant for most the past 12 years, including the last two
seasons in Charlotte. 
</P>
</TEXT>
