<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Recovery of H.K. External Trade: Long Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 9 (Xinhua Correspondent Tao Wenge) -- The
maintenance and enhancement of the advantages of flexible
management, quick response to market changes, efficient production
and timely shipment of products of Hong Kong's external trade
firms may help them achieve better performance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, the recovery of Hong Kong's external trade still has
an arduous long way to go following the sharp decrease in 1998 due
to the falling demand from its major markets caused by the
economic downturn as a result of the Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The volume of Hong Kong's total exports decreased by 4.3
percent in 1998 compared with that of 1997. The volume of re-
exports decreased by 3.7 percent, and the volume of domestic
exports by 7.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
As an open economy with elaborate trade and investment links
with the rest of Asia, Hong Kong was hit hard by the regional
financial turmoil which engulfed the region and swept beyond it.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's exports to the United States and Europe grew, but
this growth was unable to compensate for the market shrinkage in
Hong Kong's exports to East Asia including Japan, South Korea,
Taiwan and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The growing volume of products made in China's mainland being
shipped out directly from mainland ports instead of Hong Kong as
before also trimmed Hong Kong's exports performance.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 the volume of freight handled by Hong Kong ports
increased by only 1 or 2 percent while in the meantime the volume
of freight handled by ports of Shenzhen in the mainland increased
by 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Looking forward, the situation of Hong Kong's external trade in
1999 could still be difficult due to the gloomy external
environment.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang forecast the total exports of
goods to decline by 3.7 percent in real terms this year,
comprising declines of 5 percent for domestic exports and 3.5
percent for re-exports.
</P>
<P>
As for the export of services, Tsang forecast a 3 percent
growth in real terms this year, anticipating a further recovery in
tourism as well as in some other service areas.
</P>
<P>
The United States may not be able to sustain last year's robust
consumer demand created partly by its strong stock market
performance.
</P>
<P>
Brazil has recently suffered from financial instability which
may yet spill over to other economies.
</P>
<P>
A good part of Europe is still under the shadow of Russia's
earlier financial fall-out.
</P>
<P>
The demand from the European Union member states could not be
expected to increase for the trade policy of the European Union
may focus on stability as the European single currency, the euro,
was newly launched.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, although financial conditions appear to have
stabilized, domestic demand remains weak because consumers'
confidence has not restored.
</P>
<P>
The pace of economic re-vitalization in Japan will be the key
to regional recovery, but that re-vitalization remains elusive.
</P>
<P>
Finally, more products made in the mainland would be shipped
out directly from ports of the mainland rather than through Hong
Kong ports.
</P>
<P>
Is there anything the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region can do to improve the external trade
performance?
</P>
<P>
The answer is that what the government can do is very limited
in a market-oriented system as in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
However, the government can really do something. It can first
stabilize the stock and property markets, which can help restore
consumers' confidence and lower the cost to a more competitive
level.
</P>
<P>
In a market economy as Hong Kong, the government would never
give subsidiaries to certain enterprises to stimulate exports.
</P>
<P>
However, the government can further enhance its promotion of
external trade through the Trade Development Council by expanding
the scale of markets and promoting new products.
</P>
<P>
The government can promote the production efficiency of local
firms, especially the small and medium-sized enterprises by
offering technology support such as the use of computer networks
and business information.
</P>
<P>
Competition for export business from within the region is
expected to be very keen. As domestic demand is weak in almost all
the economies in the region, the development of the external trade
is very important for those economies.
</P>
<P>
Will Hong Kong fail to compete with its regional rivals? The
answer would be "no".
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is still competitive though its production cost is
relatively higher than other economies in the region due to the
devaluation of currencies in many economies of the region.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of the Hong Kong dollar can not help the external
trade because most of the raw materials were bought from outside
Hong Kong and manufacturing is not in Hong Kong, mostly in the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of Renminbi may help to reduce the cost but it's
impossible because the adjustment of Renminbi may lead to a new
round of wave of the Asian financial turmoil. The series of
reactions could impose greater threat to Hong Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's advantages include the product quality, flexibility
of management, quick response to the changes of markets,
production efficiency, timely shipment of products.
</P>
<P>
The overseas market pay more attention to the quality of the
products than prices at present because in these markets the
retail prices may be several times the prices of the imported
goods. Price may not constitute a big proportion in the overall
structure of cost of these markets.
</P>
<P>
Today it's unlikely to receive small number of orders for large
amount of goods but large number of orders for small amount of
goods.
</P>
<P>
In this circumstances, the management flexibility, production
efficiency, timely shipment would be more important than prices.
</P>
<P>
With regards to price, the Hong Kong-funded firms in the
mainland can find more cheap labor and raw materials if they move
further to the inland areas of the mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
