<HEADLINE> Ghana, Germany Sign Grant Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Ghana is to receive from Germany a
total of 15 million Deutsche marks non-repayable grants under
three agreements signed in Accra.
</P>
<P>
Kwame Peprah, Minister of Finance, signed Monday for Ghana
while Winfried Polte, senior vice-president of the German
Department of Development Loan Cooperation (KFW), signed on behalf
of his country, the Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ghana has so far received assistance totalling 1.1 billion
Deutsche marks, the equivalent of 600 million dollars, from
Germany within the framework of a financial cooperation program.
</P>
<P>
The first grant of 10 million marks is meant for water supplies
to poor areas in the Volta and Eastern Regions while the second
grant of three million marks is for basic education under which
Teacher Training Colleges at Bimbila, Pusiga and Tamale in the
Northern Region would be rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
The third grant for two million marks is for the "Study and
Expert Fund Four" which is meant to cater for costs in the
preparation of various programs for cooperation matters.
</P>
<P>
Peprah thanked the German government for its financial
assistance which had helped improve the economic status of
Ghanaians.
</P>
<P>
Ghana has a high profile for assisting investors, he said,
urging German companies to take advantage of the enabling
environment to do business in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
Ekwow Spio-Garbrah, Minister of Education, said government is
making efforts to ensure that a fee-free compulsory education by
the year 2005 succeeds.
</P>
<P>
He said success can only be real when infrastructure and
supplies are in place to provide a congenial atmosphere to train
quality teachers who will produce well educated children to
contribute toward economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
