<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motor Vehicles Cause Half of Air Pollution in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Motor vehicles are responsible for
nearly 50 percent of the air pollution in the Bangladeshi capital
city of Dhaka, endangering public health, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Some 16,000 polluting vehicles have been identified by the
Bangladesh Road Transport Authority (BRTA), Amanullah Chowdhury,
director of the BRTA, told a project-launching workshop organized
by the Dhaka Urban Transport Project on Monday, The Bangladesh
Observer reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
About 160,000 motorized vehicles are plying in the Dhaka
metropolitan area at present, with about one-third of them having
no fitness certificates and constantly emitting black smoke and
fumes polluting the air, according to the BRTA.
</P>
<P>
The air pollution has been causing serious health hazards to
the residents in the city with a population of over 9 million.
Traffic policemen and pedestrians are often seen wearing gauze
masks to cover their nose and mouth in the street to protect
themselves from inhaling hazardous air.
</P>
<P>
The level of suspended particulates in the city's air has
reached 2,600 micrograms per cubic meter, much higher than the
acceptable level, and the range of sulfur dioxide is about 100
micrograms per cubic meter against the acceptable level of 80
micrograms, according to a recent survey conducted by the
Environment Department on the air quality in the city.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the pollution level of the city, deputy director of
the department, Md. Reazuddin, said the department along with the
BRTA and police would set up 20 more check posts in some crucial
points of the city to control the smoke-emitting vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The government has already banned the import of two-stroke
engines, widely used in motor cycles and baby-taxis (three-wheeled
motorized vehicles), and are implementing a World Bank-financed
project which is expected to be completed by 2003, to improve the
city's environment through developing its transport system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
