<HEADLINE> New Zealand Minister Leaves for Japan, China, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Minister for
International Trade Lockwood Smith left here for Japan, China and
Singapore Tuesday to promote objectives for the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) 1999.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand plays host to APEC meetings this year with APEC
leader's informal meeting scheduled to be held in Auckland in
September.
</P>
<P>
Smith will chair meetings with representatives of APEC Business
Advisory Council, key business people and academics. His current
trip to Japan, China and Singapore follows his visit to Malaysia,
Thailand and Indonesia in February.
</P>
<P>
"Visiting these influential economies now will contribute
toward achieving concrete outcomes from APEC 1999," Smith said in
a statement, which was released before his departure.
</P>
<P>
"My visit to Southeast Asia in February reinforced the
importance of discussing our objectives for APEC with member
economies. I expect this trip will be equally valuable. I will
share our themes and objectives, and listen to each economy's
specific views and concerns," he said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve objectives for APEC 1999, "New Zealand
needs to build momentum behind APEC's work," Smith said. "New
Zealand's objective of broadening support for the APEC process
will be advanced through a series of roundtable discussions," he
added. 
</P>
