<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Sector Investment Not Satisfactory in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Disbursement of investment funds
in Thailand should be speeded up as the country's state
enterprises sector investment in the first quarter of the current
fiscal year has been 37 percent behind the target, a report by the
National Economic and Social Development Board (NESDB) available
Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
State enterprises sector invested 41.55 billion baht (1.12
billion U.S. dollars) in the first quarter of the current fiscal
year, which started last October, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Increasing the expenditure of state enterprises is one of the
measures being emphasized by the government to boost domestic
consumption and bring the country out of its worst economic
recession in decades.
</P>
<P>
Due to the delay in the disbursement of investment funds by
state enterprises in the first quarter, the NESDB report said it
is important to speed up the process in order to meet the
disbursement target, and stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed two major factors as the reasons for slow
disbursement of budget funds: the liquidity problem of state
enterprises, and an adjustment of their investment plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
