<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Try 2 Big Smuggling, Corruption Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Ho Chi Minh City's new Chief Judge
of the People's Court Dong Thi Anh will begin her tenure by
presiding over what should prove Vietnam's two biggest smuggling
and corruption cases, the Vietnam News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They involve a host of charges being laid against the Tan
Truong Sanh company and another private company EPCO-Minh Phung.
</P>
<P>
"Preparations are almost completed and the Tan Truong Sanh case
will be heard between the 22nd and 25th of this month, and the
EPCO-Minh Phung case should go to court in early May," Anh said.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-four alleged offenders face court regarding the
operations of Tan Truong Sanh.
</P>
<P>
Those indicted include Tran Dam, director of the trading
company, his wife and three of their children, 32 former customs
officers and 17 officials and employees of nine state-owned
import-export companies.
</P>
<P>
Under the indictment, Tran Dam and his accomplices illegally
imported 903 containers of goods through nine state-owned
import-export companies between 1994 and August 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of the 903 containers, 544 contained 77 cars, a number of
electronic products and refrigerators and electrical goods valued
at more than 900 billion Vietnamese dong (64.3 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Tran Dam is also accused of corrupting customs officers with
bribes in the form of Vietnamese dong and U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Minh Phung Company and the Export Production
Company, EPCO, up to 77 individuals will be prosecuted, most for
fraud involving state assets.
</P>
<P>
Between 1994 and 1997, the two companies bribed several banking
officials to obtain loans worth thousands of billions of
Vietnamese dong and more than 20 million U.S. dollars which they
cannot repay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
