<HEADLINE> Italy Sees Iranian President as Moderate Reformer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami,
who starts a visit to Italy Tuesday, should be seen as a "hope for
moderation and reform" in a country dominated for many years by
Islamic fundamentalism, Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said that Khatami's visit to Italy is "an event of the
utmost importance" and Khatami himself should be welcomed as an "
an important novelty" in Iran's politics.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian opposition in exile has been organizing
demonstrations against the visit, claiming that Iran's poor human
rights record has remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini later joined D'Alema's
appeal to all Italy's political parties for their support of
Khatami's reform.
</P>
<P>
"They should applaud the president against the most
conservative forces in an extremely closed Islamic state which
Khatami himself has described as religious fascism," said Dini.
</P>
<P>
"I think Khatami deserves encouragement from all the political
forces in our country," Dini added. 
</P>
