<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ho Chi Minh City Targets 4 Billion Dollars in Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam's largest
economic hub, is determined to post a 6-7 percent increase in
exports this year despite the economic slowdown, official media
here reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It has targeted a turnover of 4,020 million U.S. dollars of
which foreign-invested businesses will account for 830 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Major exports are industrial goods at 71.9 percent, (of which
garments make up 70 percent), agricultural products 20.6 percent,
forestry and sea products 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first two months of this year, export turnover
registered an increase of 12.4 percent over the same period last
year at 668 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The increase mainly resulted from a 52.3 percent growth by
foreign-invested companies.
</P>
<P>
To reach this year's target, the city will focus on the
development of food and marine product processing industries,
consumer goods production and the export-oriented sector as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City will assist and encourage all economic sectors
to join export operations. The number of exporters has risen from
900 to 1,200 over the past three months.
</P>
<P>
The city last year posted a drop of 1.9 percent in export value
from the previous year after successive years of growth.
</P>
<P>
Economists attributed the slump to the regional financial
crisis, drop in international prices, unfavorable weather
conditions and slow development of the processing industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
