<HEADLINE> German FM Urges Kosovo's Warring Sides to Accept Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 8 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Joscher
Fischer on Monday urged both the Serbs and ethnic Albanians to
sign the Rambouillet peace accord, Yugoslavia's official Tanjug
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after holding talks in Pristina
with ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova, the German foreign
minister, who is the European Union's rotating president, said, "
it is very important that we need peace here in Kosovo; we need an
end to fighting; we need an end to killing."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, Fischer held talks in Belgrade with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, who stood against the stationing of
NATO peacekeeping troops on Yugoslav territory as part of a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said it would be very hard to persuade the Serbs to
accept the accord totally, but he believed that the ethnic
Albanians would take the plan.
</P>
<P>
Fischer warned that the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) would be
making a "historical mistake" if they do not accept the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Envoy Christopher Hill, after meeting with KLA
commanders at "a secret place" in Kosovo on Monday, disclosed that
the KLA is opposed to several clauses in the peace deal, including
the KLA's weapon surrender to NATO peacekeepers. 
</P>
