<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Convenes Third Plenary Meeting (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing Second Session of
Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's legislature, held
its third plenary meeting in the Great Hall of the People in
downtown Beijing this morning.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,781 NPC deputies attended the meeting, which was
presided over by Wang Guangying, an executive chairman of both the
session and its Presidium.
</P>
<P>
The legislators heard explanations on a draft amendment to
China's Constitution, a draft contracts law and a draft method for
electing Ninth NPC deputies in the Macao Special Administrative
Region (SAR). They also heard a report on the work of the NPC
Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with a decision by the NPC Standing Committee,
Tian Jiyun, vice chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, first
explained on the draft Constitutional Amendment.
</P>
<P>
"The Constitution of the People's Republic of China adopted in
1982 is a good Constitution, which has played a vital role in the
country's political, economic and social life," said Tian.
</P>
<P>
He noted that two amendments were made to some parts of the
Constitution in 1988 and 1993 as a result of the constant
development of China's reform, opening-up and socialist
modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
After the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) convened in 1997, which made comprehensive
arrangements for advancing the cause of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics into the next century, the CPC Central
Committee suggested that an appropriate revision be made to some
parts of the Constitution in accordance with the report of the 15
th National Party Congress, said Tian.
</P>
<P>
The CPC Central Committee also suggested the principle for the
amendment, which is that changes shall be made only on issues
which require necessary revision and have been well considered,
and that no change shall be made on issues for which a revision is
not absolutely necessary, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
