<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Clears Way for New Loans for Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) said on Monday that it had agreed with Brazil on a new
economic program that would release 4.9 billion U.S. dollars for
Brazil after an executive board vote expected within weeks.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said he would recommend
to the IMF's executive board the approval of the revised program
for 1999-2001 proposed by the Brazilian government, which sees a
sharp drop in growth this year as well as falling inflation and
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"The key elements of the new program are a strengthened fiscal
adjustment and, in the light of the floating of the exchange rate,
the adoption of a new nominal anchor for monetary policy," the IMF
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The IMF put together an international rescue deal amounting to
41.5 billion dollars for Brazil's struggling economy last November
and disbursed an initial payment of 5.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It had scheduled to pay a further 4.5 billion dollars by the
end of February, but a devaluation of the real, the Brazilian
currency, in January meant the two sides had to renegotiate
conditions behind the loan.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the IMF executive board is expected to
review Brazil's new program, which sets out what Brazil will do in
return for the IMF's money, at the end of March or the beginning
of April. This is when the money is likely to be handed over to
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the IMF's decision, the World Bank said it planned to
disburse a loan of 1.01 billion dollars to Brazil to boost its
social assistance program.
</P>
<P>
In a statement welcoming the agreement between the IMF and
Brazil, U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said that "firm and
sustained implementation" of the program by Brazil can preserve
financial stability and foster growth and investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States is prepared to join the IMF and other
countries to make available substantial additional financing from
the international support program arranged last year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF gave a gloomier outlook for the Brazilian economy
compared to the forecasts the agency made in the December issue of
its World Economic Outlook, when it forecast a decline in gross
domestic product of 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Although real GDP is now expected to decline by 3.5 to 4
percent in 1999, it is expected that the program will lay the
basis for a sustained recovery in 2000 and beyond, as confidence
recovers, and external financing constraints are eased," the IMF
statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
