<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Strengthens Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
Ninth National People's Congress, the country's top law-making
body, has made substantial progress in legislation since it was
inaugurated last March.
</P>
<P>
According to a report delivered today at the ongoing NPC annual
session by the standing committee's vice chairman Jiang Chunyun on
the committee's legislative work, the NPC and its Standing
Committee examined 28 draft laws and law-related decisions last
year, out of which 11 laws and 11 law-related decisions were
adopted.
</P>
<P>
It also approved 10 agreements and treaties the Chinese
government signed with foreign countries and international
conventions acceded to by China, he said.
</P>
<P>
The most important results of its legislative work include:
draft amendments to the Constitution and a draft Contract Law to
be submitted to the current NPC session for examination, and laws
that have been enacted including the Securities Law and the
Organic Law on Villagers' Committee, he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited the following five measures taken by the legislature
to improve its legislative work:
</P>
<P>
--to make annual, five-year and long-term plans for legislation.
The NPC Standing Committee of this term has set as its goal the
establishment of a basic socialist legal framework with Chinese
characteristics by the end of this century. It also worked out a
plan for legislation in the next five years and is considering
working on an outline for legislative work from now till the year
2010;
</P>
<P>
-- to enact and amend laws under the guidance of the
Constitution and in the fundamental interests of the people and
the overall interests of the nation;
</P>
<P>
-- to take into consideration China's basic national conditions
and absorb the experience of foreign countries when enacting laws
to ensure that they incorporate the results of the reform while
leaving room for further improvement;
</P>
<P>
--to adhere to the mass line and solicit public opinion on a
broad basis. The draft law on land management and the draft of a
revised organic law on villagers' committee, for example, were
published on newspapers prior to their enactment to get comments
and suggestions from the general public;
</P>
<P>
--to improve legislation quality by spending more time on the
deliberation of bills. Drafts of laws have to undergo three rounds
of deliberations at the NPC Standing Committee before they are
adopted, as against the old practice of two rounds of
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
Talking about legislative work in years to come, Jiang said the
NPC Standing Committee of this term is expected to enact or amend
89 laws, 29 of which will be examined this year, including law on
tender invitation, law on solely-funded enterprises, trust law,
law on labor contract, law on administrative appeal and
legislation law.
</P>
<P>
"We have a tough task ahead as reforms have entered a crucial
stage," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Exams Draft Contracts Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A unified, comprehensive contracts
law was tabled at the Second Session of the Ninth National People'
s Congress (NPC) for examination here today.
</P>
<P>
Gu Angran, chairman of the Commission of Legislative Affairs
under the NPC Standing Committee, made explanations on the draft
contracts law to the NPC session today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the guidelines of drafting the contracts law are:
To draft a unified and relatively comprehensive contracts law by
preceding from China's actual conditions and absorbing useful
international experience under the guidance of Deng Xiaoping
Theory so as to guarantee healthy development of socialist market
economy;
</P>
<P>
To pay attention to maintaining coherence and consistence of
law and to supplement and perfect the contracts law by summarizing
practice experience on the basis of the existing Economic
Contracts Law, Law on Economic Contracts involving Foreign
Interests and Law on Technological Contracts;
</P>
<P>
To place importance on easiness for administration by absorbing
as many rules as possible from administrative regulations and
judicial interpretation on contracts that proved to be effective
in the past decade and making the most detailed stipulations
possible on rules that have to be added.
</P>
<P>
China has put into force three contracts laws in the past two
decades, including the Economic Contracts Law, the Law on Economic
Contracts Involving Foreign Interests and the Law on Technological
Contracts.
</P>
<P>
"These three contracts laws have made significant contributions
to safeguarding rights and interests of contract parties,
maintaining social and economic order, promoting economic growth,
technological advances and expansion of foreign economic and trade
affairs and guaranteeing smooth progress of the cause of socialist
construction," Gu said.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that as China continues reforms and
opens wider to the outside world, the regulating scopes and some
rules of the three contracts laws are no longer compatible with
new economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The draft contracts law tabled today has an enlarged regulating
scope comparing with that of the three previous contracts laws.
</P>
<P>
The basic principles that the draft contracts law stipulates
for contracts are "equality, willingness; fairness, honesty and
credibility, and law-abiding."
</P>
<P>
Gu said that the principle of willingness reflects basic
characteristics of civil activities. It is a unique principle that
marks the difference between a civil law and administrative and
criminal laws. It is also the objective requirement in developing
socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that the parties involved have the right to conclude
contracts according to their own will. However, he pointed out
that they must exert the right in line with the law. The content
and process of concluding the contracts must also be in line with
the law and administrative regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Exams Draft Contracts Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Referring to conclusion and fulfillment of contracts, he
pointed out that the rights and duties of the parties involved
should be defined by conclusion of contracts. He said that taking
every thing possible into consideration before concluding
contracts will be conducive to safeguarding the legal rights and
interests of the parties involved, reduce disputes in executing
contracts and facilitate prompt solutions to disputes in case they
crop up.
</P>
<P>
He noted that fulfillment of contracts is linked with interests
of the parties involved and significant for commodity circulation
and economic development.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the draft contracts law emphasizes the
principle of complete fulfillment of contracts. That is to say
that the parties involved have to perform their specific duties
according to agreement in contracts and either of them must not
change or stop performing the duties unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure the parties involved to fulfill contracts,
maintain trade order in market, compensate losses that incur on
other parties by violating contracts and safeguard the legitimate
rights and interests of the parties involved, the draft contracts
law goes further to perfect rules on liabilities of violation of
contracts, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This an important rule to ensure that the parties involved
will perform their duties in accordance with contracts," Gu
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The sub-provisions of the draft contracts law retain the forms
of contracts that the existing three contracts laws stipulate,
including contracts of supply and sales, electricity supply and
usage, fund lending, leasing, project undertaking, project
engineering, transport, storage and preservation and technology.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, in light of new development in economic and
trade and practice of legal trials, the draft contracts law
stipulates additional forms of contracts, including contracts of
leasing for fund raising, donation, trust, brokerage and mediation.
</P>
<P>
Gu said that the existing Economic Contracts Law, Law on
Economic Contracts Involving Foreign Interests and Law on
Technological Contracts will be ceased immediately after the new
contracts law is adopted.
</P>
<P>
Rules of previous administrative regulations, local laws and
regulations and other regulations on contracts will also be sorted
out. The rules that do not go with rules of the contracts law will
be modified, and some of them will be abolished.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15,000 Sri Lankan Villagers Freed From Tamil Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Around 15,000 Sri Lankan civilians
living in 25 villages in northern Wanni area have been liberated
from the clutches of the Tamil rebels, the official Daily News
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government troops captured about 535 square kilometers of
land under the operation "Rana Gosa" (the Sound of the War)
launched last Thursday, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It is the first government offensive since a limited operation
in early December, in which troops captured a triangular area of
land.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the troops had met with almost no resistance
from the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), although they
were ready to meet any contingency.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Anurudha Ratwatte and heads of the
security forces visited the liberated areas and mingled with the
villagers who reportedly complained that the rebels had treated
them very badly and even robbed their food rations, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Measures have been adopted to ensure adequate food supplies and
security for the civilians in the newly liberated areas, it added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a Defense Ministry press release said that troops
involved in the operation continue to dominate the newly captured
areas where rehabilitation work has been immediately started.
</P>
<P>
LTTE rebels have been waging a war against the government since
1983 for a separate state of its own in the north and east of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
