<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Remains Opposed to NATO-Led Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic said Monday a peace deal expected to be signed during
the second-stage talks in France should not let "foreign troops
police any peace accord on Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
When meeting with visiting German Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer, who serves as the rotating chairman of the European Union,
Milosevic said that the peace deal should not impose others' views
on Yugoslavia, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said Yugoslavia stood firm for a political solution to the
Kosovo issue on the basis of respect for the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of Serbia and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He added the key of a political settlement of the Kosovo issue
is to respect and uphold the equality of all ethnic groups in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
A peace conference is scheduled for March 15 after the
Rambouillet talks ended with both sides expressing reservations
over an interim autonomy plan for the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic said the issue of the international community's
presence in Kosovo has been resolved in an agreement reached last
October between Yugoslavia and the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in European (OSCE) on sending OSCE civilian observers
to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The international community has no reason to continue to put
pressure on Yugoslavia as it has been unswervingly carrying out
all international obligations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic also said he hoped that the European nations would
support the ongoing anti-terrorism struggle in Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
