<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Asks International Community to Stop Aid for Kosovo Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia on Monday urged the
international community to cut off all channels of financial and
military support for ethnic Albanian rebels fighting for the
province's independence.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with German Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer, Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic said that
cutting off the rebels' supply lines would greatly help the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had briefed Fischer on the Serbian government
delegation's preparations to continue peace talks in France this
month.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, whose country holds the rotating EU presidency, noted
that the peace agreement to be signed at the next stage must be
based on respect for Yugoslavia's sovereignty and territorial
integrity and substantial autonomy for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He called on the parties concerned to use the talks to be held
in France on March 15 to make substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian delegation, under pressure from the Western
countries, reached an outline peace agreement with the ethnic
Albanian delegation after 17 days of talks in Rambouillet near
Paris last month.
</P>
<P>
Both NATO and EU have said that the results of the first stage
of talks are not renegotiable and what the parties should discuss
is how to implement that agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
