<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Says NATO Force Indispensable to Kosovo Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Monday that a NATO force was indispensable to a Kosovo
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference that started here Monday to mark the
15-nation military alliance's 50th anniversary, Blair said a
peacekeeping force from NATO was vital to the peace agreement,
which the Contact Group on former Yugoslavia is urging the rivalry
parties in the Serbian province of Kosovo to sign as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
"Political agreement is not enough: the Balkans are littered
with agreements that are signed but not implemented," he told the
conference.
</P>
<P>
"To make an agreement work, to bring stability to Kosovo, an
international force is an indispensable element. Only NATO is
equipped to lead it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Western community wants to convene a peace conference in
France on March 15 to put the finishing touches to an interim
autonomy deal.
</P>
<P>
Last month, initial talks for peace in Kosovo ended after 17
days in France with no conclusive result.
</P>
<P>
"We will not accept prevarication in the negotiations. No side
can be allowed to obstruct the process," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Blair argued for stronger defense links between
the European Union and NATO.
</P>
<P>
"We Europeans should not expect the United States to play a
part in every disorder in our own backyard. The European Union
should be able to take on some security tasks on our own," Blair
argued.
</P>
<P>
His message was echoed by German Defense Minister Rudolf
Scharping, who set a target of two years to integrate Europe's
defense capabilities into the EU.
</P>
<P>
"It also includes integrating the Western European Union into
the EU soon. Concrete ideas on how this could be done should be
developed in the near future so that they can be implemented soon,
which means within a time frame of about two years," Scharping
said.
</P>
<P>
The United States wants its NATO allies to take a greater share
of the defense burden but is wary of French-inspired plans to give
European members independent decision-making powers.
</P>
<P>
NATO has repeatedly threatened to strike at Serb forces in and
around Kosovo if Belgrade is deemed to be blocking a deal to end
the conflict in the ethnic Albanian region.
</P>
<P>
But a settlement in Kosovo seemed as far away as ever on Monday
when the Albanians raised serious objections to the peace plan
designed by the Contact Group, which they appear unwilling to sign
up at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. senator Bob Dole, who was sent to Yugoslavia last
week as a representative of President Bill Clinton to mediate
peace in Kosovo, said in London last Saturday that Kosovo
Albanians "will" sign the peace agreement on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
