<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Manta City Possible Site for U.S. Military Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, March 8 (Xinhua)-- The harbor city of Manta, on Ecuador'
s Pacific coast, has been listed as a possible site for a U.S.
military base in South America, press reports said Monday, citing
government sources.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Jose Gallardo reportedly supports the
establishment of the U.S. military base, which he said would help
stop Colombian guerrillas from entering Ecuadoran territory and
control drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Zambrano, mayor of Manta, also spoke in favor of
installing such a base on Ecuador's coast, but argued the
installation should pay its way with important benefits for
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadoran President Jamil Mahuad will decide soon whether the
Ecuadoran government signs an agreement with the United States to
establish a military base in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. army has moved its southern command, which supervises
all military operations in the Caribbean and Latin America, from
Panama to Miami and is preparing to abandon its bases in the
Central American country before the end of this year. 
</P>
