<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Mindanao Peace Process Under Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Mindanao peace process may
suffer another setback if fierce fighting erupts between the New
People's Army and the government troops who are preparing to
rescue by force four army and police officers abducted by the
rebel group.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that more government troops are being
deployed in Mindanao, the southern Philippines, for military
operations if the New People's Army (NPA), the military wing of
the National Democratic Front (NDF), refuses to release the four
officers.
</P>
<P>
The four are Brig. Gen. Victor Obillo, Army Capt. Eduardo
Montealto, Police Chief Inspector Roberto Bernal and Army Sgt.
Alipio Lozada. They have been abducted in the past month by the
NPA, which is demanding a prison swap with the government.
</P>
<P>
Following the abduction, President Joseph Estrada indefinitely
suspended formal peace talks with the NDF, making a lasting peace
in Mindanao more distant.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said that the
rebel group should immediately release the military and police
officers without any conditions.
</P>
<P>
"The government's position is clear and simple: no ifs, no
buts, free the hostages before peace negotiations are resumed," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that if any fighting breaks out between the
two sides, it will take time for the two sides to heal the wound.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the Mindanao peace process
has been almost derailed by conflicts between the government and
the country's rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
In January, when Estrada was told that the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) wants independence, he ordered the
military to shoot back. Government troops engaged MILF rebels in a
series of bloody skirmishes that broke a 1997 cease-fire, and
turned the rebel group's home base, Maguindanao, into a no-man's
land.
</P>
<P>
In the two-week-old fighting, 60 people were killed, scores
wounded and 90,000 residents were left homeless.
</P>
<P>
In response, the 12,000-strong MILF, which has been fighting
for an independent Islamic state in Mindanao since 1978,
threatened to launch a holy war against the government.
</P>
<P>
To save the peace process, President Estrada had planned a
meeting with MILF Chairman Hashim Salamat during his trip to
Mindanao early this month.
</P>
<P>
However, Estrada canceled the meeting in the last minute
because of disputes over security arrangements. Critics said that
Estrada missed an opportunity to heal the wound by canceling the
scheduled meeting.
</P>
<P>
At present, the government is trying to woo the rebels back to
the negotiation table, but there are many obstacles lying on the
way to a lasting peace in the Southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, both the government and the rebels would not easily
make any compromise over their major objectives in the future
talks.
</P>
<P>
While the MILF is demanding the establishment of a Muslim state
in Mindanao, the government insists that the territorial integrity
is non- negotiable.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, it will take years for the government to resolve the
poverty issue in Mindanao, the root cause of insurgency in the
south.
</P>
<P>
For the past three decades, the economic development in
Mindanao has lagged behind the rest of the country, although it
produces 25 percent of the nation's rice and 70 percent of its
corn, partly because of a war, and partly because of the
government's ignorance.
</P>
<P>
Even after the government and the Moro National Liberation
Front signed a peace accord to end a 30-year-old war in Mindanao
in September 1996, the government did not allocate enough funds to
the region.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the government promised to start a series of projects
in the region, including a 266 million U.S. dollar sugar mill and
refinery, a 69 million dollar irrigation program, and a 1,400-km
railway that would circle the entire island of Mindanao. But it
would take many years to complete these projects.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the MILF and the NDF have formed an alliance against
the government in addition to other sabotage activities by Abu
Sayyaf rebels.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, some observers accused the government of failing to
adopt a flexible attitude toward rebels.
</P>
<P>
If the government fails to adopt new strategies to keep the
peace process on track, the situation in Mindanao may continue to
deteriorate in the months ahead, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts and Figures: China's Major Trade Partners in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Following are the latest facts and
figures regarding China's top ten trade partners in January
available today from the General Administration of Customs:
</P>
<P>
--Japan. Total trade volume reached 3.729 billion US dollars,
down 1.3 percent from the same month last year. Exports to Japan
were recorded at 1.781 billion US dollars, down 8.7 percent and
imports at 1.948 billion US dollars, up 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- The United States. Total trade volume hit 3.664 billion US
dollars, up 3.1 percent. China's exports to the U.S. reached 2.466
billion U.S. dollars, up 4.3 percent, and imports from the U.S.
reached 1.198 billion US dollars, up 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Hong Kong Special Administrative Region. Total trade volume
hit 2.5098 billion US dollars, down 28.5 percent. Exports to Hong
Kong dropped 33.9 percent to reach 2.033 billion US dollars, and
imports from Hong Kong grew 9.6 percent to reach 476.8 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations). Total trade
volume reached 1.770 billion US dollars, up 17.5 percent. Exports
to ASEAN declined 0.9 percent to reach 778.535 million US dollars
and imports surged 37.4 percent to 991.9 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- The Republic of Korea (ROK). Total trade volume came to 1.
559 billion US dollars, up 16.5 percent. Exports to ROK reached
475.47 million US dollars, up 7.1 percent, and imports 1.084
billion US dollars, up 21.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Taiwan. General trade volume reached 1.566 billion US
dollars, up 14.9 percent. Exports hit 261.833 million US dollars,
up 9.2 percent, and imports 1.3047 billion US dollars, up 16.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Germany. Total trade volume hit 1.072 billion US dollars, up
15.1 percent. Exports reached 566.694 million US dollars, up 2.4
percent, and imports 505.476 million US dollars, up 33.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
--Britain. Total trade volume came to 407.588 million US
dollars, down 7.0 percent. Exports to Britain declined 12.2
percent to 270.048 million US dollars, and imports rose 5.4
percent to 137.541 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
--Australia. Total trade volume surged 12.4 percent to 402.914
million US dollars. Exports to Australia reached 157.017 million
US dollars, down 9.0 percent, and imports 245.897 million US
dollars, up 32.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- The Netherlands. Total trade volume was recorded at 394.416
million US dollars, down 9.9 percent. Exports to the Netherlands
dropped 9.2 percent to 343.916 million US dollars, and imports
dropped 14.5 percent to 50.5 million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
