<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rating Downgrade Groundless: BoCom Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Communications BoCom)
regretted Standard &AMP; Poor's demotion of credit rating, regarding
it as a biased decision, today's China Daily quoted a senior
official with Bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official claimed that the credit rating agency's conclusion
was groundless, saying the Ministry of Finance has been consistent
in injecting capital to support the bank's development.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China (PBOC), China's central bank, also
spared no efforts to support CoBom since it was reconstructed into
a share-holding commercial bank in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Standard &AMP; Poor's downgraded BoCom's long-term credit rating to
BB plus on March 1.
</P>
<P>
Standard and Poor's decision does not accord with BoCom's
actual performance, the senior official said.
</P>
<P>
As of 1998, despite the adverse impact of the Asian financial
crisis, the bank still achieved an assets volume of 183.9 billion
yuan (58.8 billion US dollars), an increase of 7.6 percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The official said that BoCom's assets quality has been strictly
controlled in line with the PBOC's stipulations, and its capital
adequacy ratio is maintained higher than 8 percent, which is
required by the Bank for International Settlements.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting BoCom's achievements in all lines of its operations,
the bank was honored as China's best performing bank for 1998 by
Euromoney, a magazine recognized worldwide, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"But to our great regret, Standard and Poor's reached a
lopsided conclusion while overlooking all these hard facts," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
An absence of a thorough understanding of China's economic
development and financial reforms was the main cause behind the
credit rating demotion, said the official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Members on Preventing Financial Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- China's top advisors raised
suggestions on preventing possible financial risks amid
increasingly faster economic globalization and trade
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Members of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), who are here attending
the committee's annual session, expressed views and raised
suggestions on the subject at group discussions in the last couple
of days on Premier Zhu Rongji's government work report.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that in 1998, China maintained the stability of
its currency Renminbi and the local stock markets despite the
negative impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Professor Xiao Zhuoji of Beijing University said that, to
ensure financial security, the first thing to do is to develop the
financial sector. He attributed China's stable financial industry
to its consistent growth over the years and the supervisory and
control experience the government has gained in the last two
decades.
</P>
<P>
Economist Dong Fureng expressed concern about bad loans
extended to enterprises. He expressed appreciation for the
government's recent moves to deal with some banks and non-bank
institutions, such as investment and trust companies, that have
been engaged in irregular activities.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wang Shiying from Hunan Economic and Financial
College proposed strengthening supervision over financial
institutions and their activities, especially overseas-funded
banking institutions and financial activities that involve
operations overseas. China should make further efforts to build a
monitoring network on financial safety, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the relationship between preventing financial
risks and assisting economic development, Liu Hongru, a vice
chairman of the China Financial Society, said that banks should
not be reluctant to grant loans for fear of no repayment but that
they should also guard against lending that is too risky.
</P>
<P>
A strong support from banks is necessary for the realization of
this year's growth target, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ren Wenyan, chairman of the Shanghai Federation of Industry and
Commerce, proposed that local banks grant more loans to small and
medium-sized enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian PM Vows to Push for Signing Kosovo Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli
Majko on Monday pledged efforts to push for the signing of the
Rambouillet peace deal by the warring sides in neighboring
Yugoslavia's Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with senior officials of the Foreign
Ministry, Majko said the Rambouillet peace package, brokered by
the six-nation Contact Group in France last month, is an essential
link in the chain of events seeking to settle the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
He said Albania, through close cooperation with the
international community as well as with Kosovo's ethnic Albanians,
has changed its role as being part of the Kosovo problem to being
an active force to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of the second phase of the peace talks,
due to start on March 15, he said Albania would participate more
actively than it did in the first phase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
