<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Reiterates Demand for Punishment Over Cable Car Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'
Alema on Monday reiterated Italy's demand that those responsible
for the Mt. Cermis cable car tragedy last year be punished.
</P>
<P>
At his weekly press briefing, D'Alema said legal procedures in
the United States have not yet been completed and that even U.S.
President Bill Clinton had recognized that the United States was
responsible for the incident.
</P>
<P>
He said defense officials from both countries are re-examining
security measures to protect the civilian population near NATO
bases in Italy.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. military court acquitted marine pilot Richard Ashby of
responsibility in the death of 20 tourists killed on February 3,
1998, when his low-flying plane snipped their cable car wires.
</P>
<P>
The court ruling, based on the fact that Ashby and crew were
given incorrect maps and had instrument problems, sparked
indignation in the home countries of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Three of the victims were Italian, seven German, five Belgian,
two from Poland, two from Austria and one from Holland.
</P>
<P>
In Washington on Saturday, D'Alema urged Clinton to see that
justice was done.
</P>
<P>
Clinton apologized for the incident and said the U.S. would
offer adequate compensation.
</P>
<P>
Italian political parties have unanimously called for a review
of rules governing NATO bases in Italy and the jurisdiction of
trials in such cases.
</P>
<P>
The Italian and U.S. defense ministries have agreed to work out
new rules to prevent a recurrence of the Mt. Cermis tragedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
