<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Central Bank Cuts Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Urging the banking system to follow
its lead, The Central Bank of Philippines (BSP) reduced its key
interest rates and other term rates Monday.
</P>
<P>
The BSP's overnight lending and borrowing rates were reduced by
25 basis points to 14.25 percent and 12.25 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The rate cuts followed last week's announcement of the
inflation rate in February as having fallen to single-digit levels
-- down to 9.9 percent from 11.5 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
"We approved the rate cuts during the Monetary Board's meeting
last Wednesday," BSP Governor Gabriel Singson said Monday. "There
was a condition that the February inflation should be lower than
11.6 percent recorded in January before a reduction of BSP's
interest rates could be done."
</P>
<P>
The central bank's move and the announcement of a lower
inflation rate last month triggered an across-the-board reduction
in Treasury Bill yields in Monday's weekly auction, with the
benchmark 91-day rate falling to 12.318 percent from last week's
12.489 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 182-day rate fell to 12.637 percent from 12.742 percent,
while the 364-day rate dropped to 12.839 percent from 12.962
percent.
</P>
<P>
With the bellwether Treasury Bill rate at 12.318 percent,
commercial banks' lending rates should fall within a range of
13.818 percent to 18.818 percent, from last week's range of 13.939
percent to 18.989 percent.
</P>
<P>
A "gentlemen's agreement" still exists among commercial banks
that would set their lending rates at 1.5 - 6.5 percentage points
above the 91-day Treasury Bill rate.
</P>
<P>
A lower BSP borrowing rate should discourage banks from lending
to the central bank, while a lower BSP lending rate should
encourage them to seek more loans from the central bank which they
in turn could use to lend to borrowing clients, thus encouraging
business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
