<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls on Women to Join in Building Nation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Minister of Social Welfare,
Relief and Resettlement Brigadier-General Pyi Sone has called on
women in the country to participate in the nation-building and
all-round development projects.
</P>
<P>
Pyi Sone, who is also chairman of the Myanmar National
Committee for Women's Affairs (NCWA), made the call at a ceremony
here Monday marking the International Women's Day.
</P>
<P>
He recalled sending a Myanmar delegation to the International
Women's Conference held in Beijing in September 1995, saying that
the country has been implementing the action plans laid down at
the conference.
</P>
<P>
For the successful implementation of the plan, the Myanmar NCWA
was formed on July 3, 1996, comprising of officials of the
government, social welfare associations and women's organizations.
</P>
<P>
The day, on which the NCWA was set up, has been later observed
as Myanmar Women's Day every year, while the country started
marking the International Women's Day in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar NCWA carries out activities such as reduction of
the number of illiterate women, poverty, women's health
improvement, domestic science, prevention of violence against
women, rehabilitation and all-round development of women.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar held its first women's conference last December and
later hosted the regional consultation on violence against women
and the role of health sector in cooperation with the World Health
Organization in January this year.
</P>
<P>
Of Myanmar's total population of 46.4 million in the 1997-98
fiscal year, 23.6 million or 50.34 percent are women, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
A census conducted in 1994 showed that 46 percent of Myanmar
women above the age of 10 were in the labor force in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the national literacy rate of women has gone up to
71.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
