<HEADLINE> NATO Troops in Macedonia Reach 8,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) has now stationed 8,000 troops in Macedonia,
in preparation for an international peacekeeping force in Kosovo,
a senior NATO military official said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The number is expected to reach 10,000 this week, NATO
spokesman Major Jen Jonsen said at the NATO press center in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Most of the soldiers came from France, Britain, Germany, Italy
and the Netherlands, and others were from the United States,
Canada, Belgium, Greece and Turkey, Jonsen said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the Macedonian Information Agency, NATO'
s logistics equipment, including tanks, other vehicles and
generators, is entering Macedonia through the border with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Yugoslav province of Serbia and Kosovar
ethnic Albanians held talks on the Kosovo issue at Rambouillet
near Paris in February, which, in principle, reached some
agreement. The two sides will continue their talks on March 15 in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
NATO had planned to send some 28,000 soldiers to Kosovo after
the Serbs and the ethnic Albanians reached an agreement. However,
the Yugoslav authorities have so far refused to allow foreign
troops to enter Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
