<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Sanction Violators of Currency Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
impose sanctions against those who bring more than 5 million
rupiah (600 U.S. dollars) in or out of the country, Bank Indonesia
Governor Sjahril Sabirin said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This step is important if we are to avoid the appearance of
fake rupiah printed overseas, as well as to reduce the risk of
rupiah speculation abroad," Sabirin said on the sidelines of a
hearing with the House of Representatives over the draft bank
regulation.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions will be in the form of fines as well as
imprisonment, Sabirin was quoted by the Indonesian Observer
Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government issued the limitation through a joint decree of
the minister of finance and Bank Indonesia governor following the
monetary crisis that has rampaged through the country's economy.
Previously, the limit was set at 50,000 rupiah.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been badly hit by the regional currency turmoil
with the rupiah losing more than 70 percent of its value against
the U.S. dollar at the height of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speculators have been blamed for exacerbating the depreciation
of the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"The two previous regulations did not explicitly mention any
sanctions. Therefore all kinds of violation could go unpunished,"
Sabirin said.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions will go into effect as soon as the central bank
draft is passed into law.
</P>
<P>
"This limitation is different from foreign exchange control.
There are many kinds of foreign exchange traffic -- not only in
the form of money -- and this traffic is not yet subject to
limitation," Sabirin added.
</P>
<P>
The crisis-hit country is still committed to a free foreign
exchange regime although it also applies a monitoring system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
