<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sea Paasageway for Southwest China Inland Region Built (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- China has spent billions of U.S.
dollars on building a passageway to the sea for its southwestern
inland regions, where economic growth was long held back by
transportation difficulties, officials from these regions said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The basically completed passageway links the entire
southwestern regions, including the provinces of Sichuan, Yunnan
and Guizhou and the Chongqing Municipality and the coastal Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region which has a number of deep-water ports
along the coastline of the South China Sea, said the officials,
who are here attending the ongoing Second Session of the Ninth
National People's Congress, China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
Going through this passageway, cargo transportation from
southwest China to the Southeast Asia and other parts of the world
can spare distance by several hundred and even thousands of
kilometers compared with going via ports in Shanghai or south
China's Guangdong province, they added.
</P>
<P>
"The building of this passageway has cost the central and local
governments dearly," said NPC deputy Li Jiating, who is also
provincial governor of Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the passage consists of a railway costing nearly
20 billion yuan (about 2.5 billion U.S. dollars) between Nanning
and Kunming, capitals of Guangxi and Yunnan respectively, an
express highway which is the longest in central and western China,
and 15 berths for 10,000-ton-class vessels at three major ports in
Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, the southwestern provinces and Guangxi
region have invested another several billion yuan to have 49
separate trans-provincial highways connected with each other to
expand the coverage of the new sea passageway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sea Passageway for Southwest China Inland Region Built (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Economists here noted that in recent years, Chinese leaders
have been increasingly concerned about the country's central and
western regions which over the past two decades have lagged far
behind the eastern coastal areas in economic development.
</P>
<P>
The southwest regions, where dozens of ethnic minorities live,
have abundant reserves of coal, iron, tin, aluminum and other
natural resources. Due to geographical and historical reasons,
however, they have remained one of the country's underdeveloped
areas.
</P>
<P>
While participating in a panel discussion of the Guangxi
delegation to the current NPC session last week, Chinese President
Jiang Zemin urged all southwest China provinces to make full use
of their own advantages, give full play to the role of the newly-
built sea passageway and open wider to the outside world to
promote their economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"In response to the central government's call, all southwest
China provinces have stepped up efforts to develop industries with
their own characteristics, such as grain processing, coal mining
and tourism," said the governor of Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
NPC deputy Wang Shuqing, deputy director of the Liuzhou
Railway Administration in Guangxi, said that prompted by the
emergence of the sea passageway, the Baise Prefecture, which used
to be the poorest area in the autonomous region, has established
itself as the country's largest base for mango and winter
vegetables growing and for the aluminum industry.
</P>
<P>
"Now almost everyone in that area has been provided with
adequate food and clothing," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
