<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT0030, March 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa maintained
Monday that it is illogical for talking about separating Tanzania
following 35 years of its existence.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who is on a one-day tour to the Pemba Island under the
rule of the Zanzibar Revolutionary Government, declared that the
union between Tanganyika and Zanzibar will stay forever, sources
from Zanzibar said. (Tanzania-President-Union)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said here Monday that
it is the Palestinian leadership that should make decision on
whether to declare statehood in early May. (Egypt-Palestine-
Arafat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations is returning to Freetown,
capital of Sierra Leone, as the military and political situation
stabilizes, a U.N. special envoy said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Special representative for Sierra Leone, Francis
Okelo of Uganda, told reporters after briefing the U.N. Security
Council that "the situation in Freetown has very much stabilized."
(UN-Sierra Leone)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States has been told that Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA) leaders have approved a peace agreement for
Kosovo and "authorized its signature," the State Department said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But spokesman James Rubin remained skeptical, telling
reporters: "What we need to do is get maximum clarity from the
Kosovar Albanian side... I think I will conclude that the
agreement is signed when it's been signed." (US-Kosovo-KLA)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Supreme Court Monday left intact Timothy
McVeigh's conviction and death sentence for the 1995 Oklahoma City
bombing that killed 168 people and injured hundreds more _ the
worst such attack on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
The court, without comment, rejected an appeal in which
McVeigh argued his trial was tainted by jury misconduct and news
reports that he confessed to his lawyers. (US-Court-Conviction)
</P>
