<HEADLINE> U.S. to Condone Large Part of Nicaragua's Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton said his country will condone a large part of its debt
with Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Clinton at a meeting with Nicaraguan
politicians in Posoltega, 130 kilometers northeast of Managua, on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he has also asked the U.S. Congress to reduce
tariff barriers for all the Central American countries.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who arrived here Monday to start his four-nation tour
in Central America, is the first U.S. president to visit Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua's Foreign Minister Eduardo Montealegre said here
Monday that the bilateral debt with the United States is
relatively small, some 75 million dollars, and that the service of
this debt is frozen for 3 years.
</P>
<P>
He said that what's important is U.S. support in international
organisms to condone Nicaragua's external debt, which stands at 6
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has already said it is disposed to reduce by
90 percent Nicaragua's debt, but this must be formalized and a
hundred percent may be achieved, better still," said Montealegre.
</P>
