<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Move in Anti-Euro Campaign in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition Conservative
Party Monday opened a new phase of its battle to prevent Britain
from joining Europe's single currency on Monday by setting up a
commission to examine the benefits of keeping sterling.
</P>
<P>
Conservative leader William Hague told a news conference the
commission, under former trade secretary Sir John Nott, would look
at how Britain could prosper if it chose to retain the pound.
</P>
<P>
Hague has ruled out Conservative support for Britain adopting
the euro in the current parliament or the next, which could mean
as late as 2007, according to local median reports.
</P>
<P>
A vast majority of Conservative members supported this policy
in a ballot last year, but party heavyweights such as former
deputy prime minister Michael Heseltine and ex-finance minister
Kenneth Clarke have publicly supported the euro.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has promised a referendum on whether
Britain adopts the euro, Hague claimed that by publishing a
National Changeover Plan last month, Prime Minister Tony Blair was
trying to push Britons into going along with the idea.
</P>
<P>
"He wants to change the cash registers, change the computer
software, change the banking systems so that in the end he can
turn round to the British people and say that they have no choice
but to change their currency," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nott said the commission wanted "to establish the facts to
convince businessmen, in particular, that we can continue to
prosper with an independent currency".
</P>
<P>
It would consider trade flows, how sterling could stand alone
beside the euro and the dollar, and the experiences of other
stand-alone currencies, the Canadian dollar within the North
American Free Trade Association, and the Swiss franc.
</P>
<P>
It would also examine what status should be given to the Bank
of England if the pound remained, the position of the City of
London banking district and how Britain outside the euro could
remain a magnet for inward investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Index Moves Down Slightly On Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Dow Jones industrial average
moved own slightly Monday after last week's strong rally.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading, the dow fell 8.47 to 9,727.61. Last
Friday, the blue chip index shot up 268.68 points at a record
high of 9,736.08, smashing the previous high of 9,643.32 set on
January 8.
</P>
<P>
The technology stocks were pushed higher after Intel, the
world's largest computer chipmaker, announced an agreement which
settled government charges against the company of illegally
bullying three other companies into handing over secret
information about their products. The technology heavy Nasdaq
index closed at 2,397.62, up 60.51 and the composite got 44.22
points in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index rose 7.26 to 1,282.73 and the NYSE index rose 0.96 to
604.10.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange index was up 4.77 at 712.18
while the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was up 2.05 at
400.06.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,368 up, 1,638 down and 561
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 705 million shares from 828 million
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
