<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada To Send Special Envoy To Assess Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Monday that it
will send a special envoy to assess the political, humanitarian
and security situation in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy, Parliament Member David Pratt named by
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworhy Monday, will travel to New York on
March 12 for discussions with UN and other officials in an effort
to restore peace and stability in Sierra Leone. He then plans to
travel to Freetown, Sierra Leone, and Conakry, Guinea later this
month.
</P>
<P>
"Canada remains concerned about the atrocities committed upon
civilians, including women and children, by the rebel groups,"
said Axworthy in a release.
</P>
<P>
"These visits will give Mr. Pratt the opportunity to see
first-hand how Canada can best support efforts to rebuild peace
and stability, and provide humanitarian assistance in Sierra
leone. We are exploring the means for providing additional support
to civilians, particularly children," added the Minister.
</P>
<P>
In New York, Pratt will meet with Francis Okello, Special
Representative of the Secretary-General for Sierra Leone, and with
Fode M.Dabor, Charge d'Affaires of the Republic of Sierra Leone,
as well as other official representatives.
</P>
<P>
This visit is in preparation for the mission to West Africa,
which will aid Pratt in making recommendations to the Minister
before Axworthy participates in the Commonwealth Ministerial
Action Group(CMAG) in London on April 29 and 30.
</P>
<P>
Sierra leone is one of the three countries under review by the
CMAG, which has a mandate to recommend collective Commonwealth
responses to serious or persistent violations of the principles
contained in the harare Declaration on human rights and democracy.
</P>
<P>
As a Security Council member, Canada will also support the
extension of the UN Observer Mission in Sierra Leone(UNOMSIL),
which is due for renewal later this week, said the release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
