<DOCNO> XIE19990309.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Stages Comeback in Freetown as Situation Stabilizes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is
returning to Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, as the military
and political situation stabilizes, a U.N. special envoy said here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Special representative for Sierra Leone, Francis Okelo
of Uganda, told reporters after briefing the U.N. Security Council
that "the situation in Freetown has very much stabilized."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Nigerian-led West African peacekeepers, known
as ECOMOG, and the Sierra Leonean Government troops intended to
"pursue this process into the other parts of the country as well."
</P>
<P>
The rebels invaded Freetown on January 6, unleashing more than
fighting before being flushed out of the capital into surrounding
suburbs and adjacent hills by ECOMOG troops.
</P>
<P>
Up to 5,000 people were killed during the invasion and vast
areas of the city were razed by rebel-set fires, reports said. The
fighting forced the United Nations to evacuate its small observer
mission to neighboring Guinea.
</P>
<P>
An advance party was in Freetown on Monday to prepare for the
mission's return, Okelo said, adding that U.N. relief agencies
also planned to return to Freetown to resume their work there "and
hopefully in the rest of the country."
</P>
<P>
A senior British envoy said here on Monday that the 15-member
Security Council is expected to make a decision on the extension
of the mandate of the U.N. Observer Mission in Sierra Leone
(UNOMSIL) on Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
