<HEADLINE> Tanzania President Guards Tanganyika-Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 8 (Xinhua) --Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa maintained Monday that it is illogical for talking about
separating Tanzania following 35 years of its existence.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who is on a one-day tour to the Pemba Island under the
rule of the Zanzibar Revolutionary Government, declared that the
union between Tanganyika and Zanzibar will stay forever, sources
from Zanzibar said.
</P>
<P>
During a private session with the ruling party Chama Cha
Mapinduzi (CCM) elders, Mkapa said that both the mainland and
Zanzibar isles could help each other in the cause of implementing
their development programs.
</P>
<P>
"After all these years, there is no available forum both on the
mainland and in Zanzibar where one could speak against the union,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Mkapa said the union government would pull
its resources together with those of Zanzibar government in ending
all inconveniences to the residents of Pemba who suffer from
electricity problem and poor state of roads.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when inspecting the electricity generating
plant at Wesha in Pemba, one of the two main parts of the Zanzibar
islands in western Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Tanganyika merged with Zanzibar, forming a union -- the United
Republic of Tanzania in 1964. According to the Tanzanian
constitution, the union has a president and a vice-president while
Zanzibar is ruled by its own president.  
</P>
</TEXT>
